in Sangokuden Trinity set \u3010Ryuuteiken Awakening ver.\u3011: \u771f \u4e09\u56fd\u4f1d\u4e09\u4f4d\u4e00\u4f53 \u3010\u9f8d\u5e1d\u5263\u899a\u9192\u7248\u3011 ([[Liu Bei]], [[Zhang Fei]], [[Guan Yu]]) (similar to BBW010, except in their evolved armours, Ryuuteiken is in metallic gold finish)\n*037. Shin Kakuka Virsago: \u771f \u90ed\u5609 ([[Guo Jia]]) (can combine with Kaku in BBW031, similar to the satellite cannon combo of the two in Gundam X, comes with a set of new eye decals)\n*038. Shin Gurensou Sousou Gundam\u30fbTengyokugai Enhou: \u771f \u7d05\u84ee\u88c5 \u66f9\u64cd\u30fb\u5929\u7389\u93a7 \u708e\u9cf3 ([[Cao Cao]]) (comes with finishing move effects, Sousou is in metallic dark-red finish)\n*039. Shin Koumei Re-GZ: \u771f \u5b54\u660e ([[Zhuge Liang|Kong Ming (aka Zhuge Liang)]]) (comes with finishing move effects, and a set of new eye decals)\n*040. Shin Kan-pei Gundam: \u771f \u95dc\u5e73 ([[Guan Ping]]) (comes with a set of new eye decals, new Ryuu flag decal, and special decals for BBW020 and BBW028)\n*041. Shin Choukou Zaku III: \u771f \u5f35\u90c3 ([[Zhang He]])\n*'''042. Shin Shouretsutei Ryuusou Ryuubi Gundam Ryuukihou\u30fbTekiro: \u771f \u7fd4\u70c8\u5e1d \u9f8d\u88dd \u5289\u5099 \u9f8d\u8f1d\u5b9d\u30fb\u7684\u76e7 ([[Liu Bei]])''' (This kit is not the same as BB318 Shouretsutei Ryuubi Gundam. The Ryuukihou is a lot more elaborate, is added onto Ryuusou Ryuubi Gundam, and can combine with Tekiro to form the soul of the Ryuutei)\n*'''043. Shin Kougai Gouf: \u771f \u9ec3\u84cb ([[Huang Gai]])'''\n*044. Shin Gurensou Sousou Gundam VS Moukosou Sonken Gundam \u3010[[Battle of Red Cliffs]] set\u3011: \u771f \u7d05\u84ee\u88c5 \u66f9\u64cd VS \u731b\u864e\u88c5 \u5b6b\u6a29 \u3010\u8d64\u58c1\u306e\u6226\u3044\u3011 ([[Cao Cao]], [[Sun Quan]]) (Sousou is in metallic red and silver finish, comes with Tenhou Itenken (\u5929\u9cf3\u5a01\u5929\u5263) and Tenhou Seihouken (\u5929\u9cf3\u661f\u51f0\u5263), combining both to become Tenhou Shichiseizou (\u5929\u9cf3\u4e03\u661f\u69cd). Sonken is in metallic gold finish, comes with Tenka Koteitou (\u5929\u83ef\u864e\u9320\u5200))\n*'''045. Shin Gouka Shouretsutei Ryuusou Ryuubi Gundam: \u771f \u8c6a\u83ef \u7fd4\u70c8\u5e1d \u9f8d\u88dd \u5289\u5099 ([[Liu Bei]])''' (Twice the size of BBW042)\n*046. Shin Shouretsutei Ryuusou Ryuubi Gundam\u30fbTengyokugai Souryuu: \u771f \u7fd4\u70c8\u5e1d \u9f8d\u88c5 \u5289\u5099\u30fb\u5929\u7389\u93a7 \u84bc\u9f8d ([[Liu Bei]]) (comes with finishing move effects)\n\n:'''Upcoming Gundams'''\n\n:'''Rumored Gundams'''\n*'''???. Shin Gouka Gurensou Sousou Gundam: \u771f \u8c6a\u83ef \u7d05\u9023\u88dd \u66f9\u64cd ([[Cao Cao]])''' (Twice the size of BBW022)\n*'''???. Shin Gouka Moukosou Sonken Gundam: \u771f \u8c6a\u83ef \u731b\u864e\u88c5 \u5b6b\u6a29 ([[Sun Quan]])''' (Twice the size of BBW023)\n\n:'''Special/Limited Edition'''\n* Ryuubi Gundam (Snow equipment): \u5289\u5099 (\u96ea\u5c71\u88dd\u5099) ([[Liu Bei]]) (packaged with the manga, {{nihongo|SD Gundam Sangokuden Brave Battle Warriors Genesis Ryuubi Chapter|\uff33\uff24\u30ac\u30f3\u30c0\u30e0\u4e09\u56fd\u4f1d Brave Battle Warriors \u5275\u4e16\u8a18(\u30b2\u30cd\u30b7\u30b9) \u5289\u5099\u7de8}}, and comes with extra parts to create Chouyopei GM (\u5f35\u4e16\u5e73\u30b8\u30e0), based on [[Zhang Shiping]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://album.blog.yam.com/muso&folder=7656076|title=yam\u5929\u7a7a\u90e8\u843d|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref>\n* Shin Kouseki Turn-X VS Ryuuhou Ryuubi Gundam set: \u771f \u9805\u7fbd VS \u5289\u90a6\u5289\u5099 ([[Xiang Yu]], [[Emperor Gaozu of Han|Liu Bang]]) (packaged with the Nintendo DS game, {{nihongo|SD Gundam Sangokuden Brave Battle Warriors Shin Mirisha Taisen|SD\u30ac\u30f3\u30c0\u30e0\u4e09\u56fd\u4f1d Brave Battle Warriors \u771f\u4e09\u7483\u7d17\u5927\u6226}}, as a limited edition boxset)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://album.blog.yam.com/muso&folder=7843476|title=yam\u5929\u7a7a\u90e8\u843d|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref>\n* Roshuku Mark III: \u9b6f\u8085\u30de\u30fc\u30afIII ([[Lu Su]]) (packaged with the manga, {{nihongo|SD Gundam Sangokuden Brave Battle Warriors Genesis Sonsaku\u2027Shuuyu Chapter|\uff33\uff24\u30ac\u30f3\u30c0\u30e0\u4e09\u56fd\u4f1d Brave Battle Warriors \u5275\u4e16\u8a18(\u30b2\u30cd\u30b7\u30b9) \u5b6b\u7b56\u2027\u5468\u745c\u7de8}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://album.blog.yam.com/muso&folder=8316972|title=yam\u5929\u7a7a\u90e8\u843d|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref>\n* Shin Chou-sen Qubeley: \u771f \u8c82\u8749\u30ad\u30e5\u30d9\u30ec\u30a4 ([[Diaochan]]) (packaged with the Blu-ray set, {{nihongo|SD Gundam Sangokuden Brave Battle Warriors Collection Box|\uff33\uff24\u30ac\u30f3\u30c0\u30e0\u4e09\u56fd\u4f1d BraveBattleWarriors \u30b3\u30ec\u30af\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u30dc\u30c3\u30af\u30b9}}, out on June 24, 2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dbeat.bandaivisual.co.jp/sangokuden-bd/ |title=\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fb\u7279\u64ae\u7b49\u6620\u50cf\u4f5c\u54c1\u306a\u3089\u30d0\u30f3\u30c0\u30a4\u30d3\u30b8\u30e5\u30a2\u30eb\u3010\u516c\u5f0f\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8\u3011 |publisher= |accessdate=17 July 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305170633/http://dbeat.bandaivisual.co.jp/sangokuden-bd/ |archivedate=5 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n=== Sangokuden \"Kiba\" Breakers ===\n\nA new sub-line was also announced, the motorised Kiba Break. Depicting popular characters such as Ryuubi and Ryofu on horseback, the kits are used in a ''jousting'' style game where players attempt to knock their opponent out. The kits come with limited figurines of their riders but can support the full model kits in their place. The line was promoted in the Brave Battle Warriors anime (in Episode 14), in the form of a new elite horse-mounted team led by Chou-un.\n\nThe following have been released so far:\n\n* \"Kiba\" Breaker Ryuubi Gundam with Hakugin Ryuuseiba: \u5289\u5099\n* \"Kiba\" Breaker Ryofu Tallgeese with Sekitoba: \u5442\u5e03\n* \"Kiba\" Breaker Kan-u Gundam with Hakugin Ryuuseiba: \u95dc\u7fbd\n* \"Kiba\" Breaker Chouhi Gundam with Hakugin Ryuuseiba: \u5f35\u98db\n* \"Kiba\" Breaker Equestrian Arena\n* \"Kiba\" Breaker Ryuubi Gundam with Ryofu Tallgeese Horse Duel Set: \u5289\u5099 + \u5442\u5e03\n* \"Kiba\" Breaker Sousou Gundam with Zetsuei: \u66f9\u64cd\n* \"Kiba\" Breaker Sonken Gundam with Hakugin Ryuuseiba: \u5b6b\u6a29\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080509080750/http://bandai-hobby.net/sangokuden/index.html Official site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080828045222/http://www.bandai-asia.com/sangokuden/ Asia official site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071220014530/http://bombom.kodansha.co.jp/?module=Manga&action=List&list_id=57 Comic Bom Bom Site]\n*[http://www.sdgundam3gd.net/ Official site for the Brave Battle Warriors anime]\n\n{{Super Deformed Gundam}}\n{{Romance of the Three Kingdoms}}\n\n[[Category:2007 manga]]\n[[Category:K\u014dichi Tokita]]<!-- manga adaptation -->\n[[Category:Works based on Romance of the Three Kingdoms]]\n[[Category:SD Gundam]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed unsupported cite parameter deadurl to url-status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BB_Senshi_Sangokuden"}
{"title_page": "Ford Police Interceptor (variant)", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Ford Police Interceptor\n| manufacturer = [[Ford Motor Company]]\n| production = 1992-present\n| class = [[Police car]]\n}}\n\n'''Ford Police Interceptor''' cars are [[police car]] variants of their originating cars, which are manufactured by [[Ford Motor Company]]. Like regular cars, all Police Interceptors go through as predecessors and successors.{{Clarify|reason=This could be put more clearly - what is the point that is trying to be made?|date=October 2017}}\n\n== Before the Police Interceptor ==\nPolice versions from Ford were originally sold, but had never used the Police Interceptor name. The cars were made from 1979 up to 1991 as the Ford LTD Crown Victoria (not an official Crown Victoria, due to it originally just being a name). These cars used the \"P72\" production code designation for [[Fleet vehicle|fleet]], taxi, and police models.\n\n== Crown Victoria (1999-2011) ==\n{{Main|Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor}}\n\n=== First generation (1992-1997) ===\n[[File:Tifton Police Vehicle 1.JPG|left|thumb|([[Tifton Police]]) The [[Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor]] was the first Police Interceptor, first released in 1992.]]\nThe [[Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor|Crown Victoria]] was the first car of the Police Interceptor lineup. The first units were released in 1992, with a 4.6-liter [[Ford Modular engine|Modular]] V8 engine and either a [[Ford AOD transmission|Ford AOD/AOD-E]] or a [[Ford 4R70W transmission|Ford 4R70W]], which were both 4-speed automatic transmissions.\n\nAlthough the Crown Victoria did have police versions back in 1979 up to 1991, the car never used the Police Interceptor moniker. Those older versions, including fleet and taxi, were known as \"P72\" in production code. 1992 was the first year the Police Interceptor name was ever used, with these known as the ''Crown Victoria P71''.\n\nThroughout 1993 to 1995, many restyles had come in. The car was updated with a front chrome grille, and also included a reflector strip between the taillights. The license plate location was moved to the rear trunk for 1995.\n\nIn the years 1994-1995, 140 of the P71 cars had entered Russia, serving for the [[Main Directorate for Road Traffic Safety (Russia)|Main Directorate for Road Traffic Safety]] (known under its abbreviation \u0413\u0410\u0418, GAI in English), which is a Russian [[law enforcement agency]], part of the [[police]]. They were operated by the [[Russia]]n [[Highway patrol|Traffic Patrol]], known in Russia as DPS, and the cars worked as highway patrol units around the greater [[Moscow]] area until the 2010s, being one of the most powerful vehicles used by the DPS.<ref name=\"dps\">''Ford Crown Victoria DPS GAI'', \"Avtomobil Na Sluzhbie\", Nr. 59, DeAgostini, 2014, ISSN 2223-0440, p.10-14 {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\n=== Second generation (1998-2011) ===\n[[File:Ford Crown Victoria police.jpg|left|thumb|([[Prince William County Police Department]]) The second generation Crown Victoria came out in 1998, with updated technology and new parts.]]\nThe Crown Victoria was restyled for the 1998 year, taking the conservative styling of the [[Mercury Grand Marquis]]. The car also went through many changes during its 13-year generation.\n\nFor 1998, the P71 police package adopted many chrome areas for the car. For 1999, a chrome-trimmed gloss black rear fascia, unpainted door handle trim, black bumper strips, and a gloss black slatted grille were introduced. The new \"Street Appearance Package\", intended to make the Police Interceptor look like a P73 model, was introduced as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.p71owners.com|title=Police Interceptor Information|publisher=p71owners.com}}</ref>\n[[File:Unmarked police cruiser with lights.jpg|thumb|An unmarked Crown Vic Police Interceptor in [[Toronto]] in 2014]]\n\nFor 2000, the rear fascia and tail-lights lost the chrome trim, and the gloss black grille was put away for a flat black slatted grille. Further changes were made in 2001, including taking off all trim on the plastic bumper pieces and a new honeycomb-style grille, replacing the slat-style grille, which is found on previous standard Crown Victorias and CVPIs. Power adjustable pedals also became an option during that year, as many officers had been joining departments with different kinds of heights. They also relocated the rear window defrost switch from the left side of the dash to the direct left of the HVAC controls. For the year 2003, interior door panels and seats were freshened, with side-impact airbags becoming an option. The suspension, brakes, steering, and frame all were redesigned for the 2003 model year. Wheels had a different offset, and the cassette player was eliminated for the 2004 year.\n\nIn 2006, the front fascia was revised with a new \"honeycomb\" grille, and the instrument panel was redesigned with a new message center and digital odometer/trip meter. New seventeen-inch (17\") plastic wheel covers were introduced for the P71, and a new steering wheel design was also introduced.\n\n2011 was the final [[model year]] for the [[Ford Crown Victoria]] Police Interceptor, as [[St. Thomas Assembly]], where the [[Ford Panther platform]] cars were produced, would close, and all three Panther Platform cars would be discontinued. The Crown Victoria Police Interceptor would be replaced by the [[Ford Taurus]]-based [[Ford Police Interceptor Sedan]] for the 2013 [[model year]], and a [[Ford Explorer]]-based [[Ford Police Interceptor Utility]] would also be introduced.\n\n== Taurus (2012-2019) ==\nTo replace the Crown Victoria, Ford used the [[Ford Taurus (sixth generation)|sixth generation Taurus]] and the [[Ford Explorer|fifth and sixth generation Ford Explorer]]. The names for both cars were instead the \"Police Interceptor Sedan\" and \"Police Interceptor Utility,\" in lieu of Taurus or Explorer. The [[Ford Police Interceptor Sedan]] was discontinued after the 2019 [[model year]].\n\n=== Ford Police Interceptor Sedan ===\n{{Main|Ford Police Interceptor Sedan}}\n[[File:Canada Day 2015 on Saint Catherine Street - 066.jpg|left|thumb|([[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]) The [[Ford Taurus (sixth generation)|Ford Police Interceptor Sedan]] was one of two cars to replace the Crown Victoria. The Sedan is based on the Ford Taurus.]]\nThe Sedan, along with the Utility came to police forces in the 2012 and 2013 model years.\n\nThe Sedan's standard engine is taken from the Ford Mustang, a 3.7-liter [[Aluminium|aluminum]]-block [[V6 engine|V6]] engine that weighed {{Convert|18|kg|lbs|0|abbr=on}} less than the previous version. The engine had 24 valves and TiVCT (Twin Independent Variable Cam Timing). It produced {{Convert|305|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|280|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque. The 3.7-liter engine came with a new dual exhaust; gasoline mileage increased to 19 city and 31 highway mpg. Ford also offers the [[Ford EcoBoost engine|EcoBoost]] version, the [[Ford Taurus SHO|SHO]]'s 3.5-liter V6 which produces {{Convert|365|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"fordcop\">{{cite web|title=EcoBoost Engines Give New Ford Police Vehicles Power and Efficiency|website=News and Events / All News|publisher=[[Ford Motor Company]]}}</ref> Both versions came with all-wheel drive. In 2014, Ford began offering the 4-cylinder engine from its civilian counterpart in the Police Interceptor Sedan as part of a Special Service trim designed for detective and administrative uses.<ref>http://lowersouthampton.patch.com/articles/police-look-for-crown-victoria-replacement</ref> The Police Interceptor includes Ford's latest safety technology, like the Blind Spot Information System, rear view camera, reverse sensing system, and electronic stability control.\n\nIn 2015, Ford considered ending production of the Taurus in the United States.  However, the Police Interceptor Sedan was a major reason for continuing production.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bunkley|first=Nick|date=17 August 2015|title=The Taurus comeback story: Is it the end for ex-champ?|journal=[[Automotive News]]}}</ref>{{Clear}}\n\nIn 2018, [[Ford]] announced that it would be ending production of the [[Ford Taurus]] sedan on which the [[Ford Police Interceptor Sedan]] was based. In March of 2019, both the Taurus and Police Interceptor Sedan were discontinued. The Police Interceptor Sedan will be replaced by the second-generation, 2020 [[Ford Explorer]]-based [[Ford Police Interceptor Utility]], as well as the [[Ford Fusion Hybrid]] Police Responder, which was introduced for the 2019 [[model year]].\n\n=== Ford Fusion Hybrid Police Responder ===\n\nFor the 2019 [[model year]], a new \"Police Responder\" was introduced, based on the second-generation [[Ford Fusion]] [[Hybrid]]. The Fusion Hybrid Police Responder is the first pursuit-rated [[Hybrid Electric Vehicle]] (HEV).\n\n== Explorer (2012-Present) ==\n\n=== Ford Police Interceptor Utility ===\n{{Main|Ford Police Interceptor Utility}}\n[[File:Bellingham, WA Police- Ford Police Utility (17266247122).jpg|left|thumb|('''[[Bellingham Police Department]])''' The [[Ford Explorer|Ford Police Interceptor Utility]] was the second of two cars to replace the Crown Victoria. The Utility is based on the Ford Explorer.]]\nThe Utility was sold to police forces in 2012 and 2013, like the Taurus, although retail isn't available.\n\nThe Utility used the 3.7-liter V6 from the Ford Mustang, which produced {{Convert|305|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}. The car then featured the Ecoboost engine from the SHO in 2014, producing {{Convert|365|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.ford.com/news-center/press-releases-detail/hot-selling-ford-police-interceptor-utility-vehicle-now-offers-3|title=Ford Motor Company Official Global Corporate Homepage &#124; Ford.com|author=|date=2017-03-13|website=Corporate.ford.com|accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\nThe Utility comes with provisions for the fitment of emergency equipment such as guns, batons, tasers, radios, first aid kits, [[lightbar]]s and sirens. To free up interior space on the center console for equipment, the transmission is fitted with a column-mounted shifter. Other fleet-specific options are included as well. It also comes with an all-wheel drive powertrain as standard, and is also fitted with larger brake rotors, more advanced ABS and traction control systems, a more efficient cooling system and other standard police equipment.{{Clear}}\n\nIn 2019, for the 2020 [[model year]], the second-generation [[Ford Police Interceptor Utility]] was introduced with a new Rear Wheel Drive (RWD)-based platform, based on the sixth-generation [[Ford Explorer]] mid-size crossover [[SUV]]. It will replace the [[Ford Police Interceptor Sedan]] in [[Ford]]'s lineup as their \"purpose-built\" police vehicle.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Police vehicles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Ford Police Interceptor\n| manufacturer = [[Ford Motor Company]]\n| production = 1992-present\n| class = [[Police car]]\n}}\n\n'''Ford Police Interceptor''' cars are [[police car]] variants of their originating cars, which are manufactured by [[Ford Motor Company]]. Like regular cars, all Police Interceptors go through as predecessors and successors.{{Clarify|reason=This could be put more clearly - what is the point that is trying to be made?|date=October 2017}}\n\n== Before the Police Interceptor ==\nPolice versions from Ford were originally sold, but had never used the Police Interceptor name. The cars were made from 1979 up to 1991 as the Ford LTD Crown Victoria (not an official Crown Victoria, due to it originally just being a name). These cars used the \"P72\" production code designation for [[Fleet vehicle|fleet]], taxi, and police models.\n\n== Crown Victoria (1999-2011) ==\n{{Main|Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor}}\n\n=== First generation (1992-1997) ===\n[[File:Tifton Police Vehicle 1.JPG|left|thumb|([[Tifton Police]]) The [[Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor]] was the first Police Interceptor, first released in 1992.]]\nThe [[Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor|Crown Victoria]] was the first car of the Police Interceptor lineup. The first units were released in 1992, with a 4.6-liter [[Ford Modular engine|Modular]] V8 engine and either a [[Ford AOD transmission|Ford AOD/AOD-E]] or a [[Ford 4R70W transmission|Ford 4R70W]], which were both 4-speed automatic transmissions.\n\nAlthough the Crown Victoria did have police versions back in 1979 up to 1991, the car never used the Police Interceptor moniker. Those older versions, including fleet and taxi, were known as \"P72\" in production code. 1992 was the first year the Police Interceptor name was ever used, with these known as the ''Crown Victoria P71''.\n\nThroughout 1993 to 1995, many restyles had come in. The car was updated with a front chrome grille, and also included a reflector strip between the taillights. The license plate location was moved to the rear trunk for 1995.\n\nIn the years 1994-1995, 140 of the P71 cars had entered Russia, serving for the [[Main Directorate for Road Traffic Safety (Russia)|Main Directorate for Road Traffic Safety]] (known under its abbreviation \u0413\u0410\u0418, GAI in English), which is a Russian [[law enforcement agency]], part of the [[police]]. They were operated by the [[Russia]]n [[Highway patrol|Traffic Patrol]], known in Russia as DPS, and the cars worked as highway patrol units around the greater [[Moscow]] area until the 2010s, being one of the most powerful vehicles used by the DPS.<ref name=\"dps\">''Ford Crown Victoria DPS GAI'', \"Avtomobil Na Sluzhbie\", Nr. 59, DeAgostini, 2014, ISSN 2223-0440, p.10-14 {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\n=== Second generation (1998-2011) ===\n[[File:Ford Crown Victoria police.jpg|left|thumb|([[Prince William County Police Department]]) The second generation Crown Victoria came out in 1998, with updated technology and new parts.]]\nThe Crown Victoria was restyled for the 1998 year, taking the conservative styling of the [[Mercury Grand Marquis]]. The car also went through many changes during its 13-year generation.\n\nFor 1998, the P71 police package adopted many chrome areas for the car. For 1999, a chrome-trimmed gloss black rear fascia, unpainted door handle trim, black bumper strips, and a gloss black slatted grille were introduced. The new \"Street Appearance Package\", intended to make the Police Interceptor look like a P73 model, was introduced as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.p71owners.com|title=Police Interceptor Information|publisher=p71owners.com}}</ref>\n[[File:Unmarked police cruiser with lights.jpg|thumb|An unmarked Crown Vic Police Interceptor in [[Toronto]] in 2014]]\n\nFor 2000, the rear fascia and tail-lights lost the chrome trim, and the gloss black grille was put away for a flat black slatted grille. Further changes were made in 2001, including taking off all trim on the plastic bumper pieces and a new honeycomb-style grille, replacing the slat-style grille, which is found on previous standard Crown Victorias and CVPIs. Power adjustable pedals also became an option during that year, as many officers had been joining departments with different kinds of heights. They also relocated the rear window defrost switch from the left side of the dash to the direct left of the HVAC controls. For the year 2003, interior door panels and seats were freshened, with side-impact airbags becoming an option. The suspension, brakes, steering, and frame all were redesigned for the 2003 model year. Wheels had a different offset, and the cassette player was eliminated for the 2004 year.\n\nIn 2006, the front fascia was revised with a new \"honeycomb\" grille, and the instrument panel was redesigned with a new message center and digital odometer/trip meter. New seventeen-inch (17\") plastic wheel covers were introduced for the P71, and a new steering wheel design was also introduced.\n\n2011 was the final [[model year]] for the [[Ford Crown Victoria]] Police Interceptor, as [[St. Thomas Assembly]], where the [[Ford Panther platform]] cars were produced, would close, and all three Panther Platform cars would be discontinued. The Crown Victoria Police Interceptor would be replaced by the [[Ford Taurus]]-based [[Ford Police Interceptor Sedan]] for the 2013 [[model year]], and a [[Ford Explorer]]-based [[Ford Police Interceptor Utility]] would also be introduced.\n\n== Taurus (2012-2019) ==\nTo replace the Crown Victoria, Ford used the [[Ford Taurus (sixth generation)|sixth generation Taurus]] and the [[Ford Explorer|fifth and sixth generation Ford Explorer]]. The names for both cars were instead the \"Police Interceptor Sedan\" and \"Police Interceptor Utility,\" in lieu of Taurus or Explorer. The [[Ford Police Interceptor Sedan]] was discontinued after the 2019 [[model year]].\n\n=== Ford Police Interceptor Sedan ===\n{{Main|Ford Police Interceptor Sedan}}\n[[File:Canada Day 2015 on Saint Catherine Street - 066.jpg|left|thumb|([[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]) The [[Ford Taurus (sixth generation)|Ford Police Interceptor Sedan]] was one of two cars to replace the Crown Victoria. The Sedan is based on the Ford Taurus.]]\nThe Sedan, along with the Utility came to police forces in the 2012 and 2013 model years.\n\nThe Sedan's standard engine is taken from the Ford Mustang, a 3.7-liter [[Aluminium|aluminum]]-block [[V6 engine|V6]] engine that weighed {{Convert|18|kg|lbs|0|abbr=on}} less than the previous version. The engine had 24 valves and TiVCT (Twin Independent Variable Cam Timing). It produced {{Convert|305|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|280|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque. The 3.7-liter engine came with a new dual exhaust; gasoline mileage increased to 19 city and 31 highway mpg. Ford also offers the [[Ford EcoBoost engine|EcoBoost]] version, the [[Ford Taurus SHO|SHO]]'s 3.5-liter V6 which produces {{Convert|365|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"fordcop\">{{cite web|title=EcoBoost Engines Give New Ford Police Vehicles Power and Efficiency|website=News and Events / All News|publisher=[[Ford Motor Company]]}}</ref> Both versions came with all-wheel drive. In 2014, Ford began offering the 4-cylinder engine from its civilian counterpart in the Police Interceptor Sedan as part of a Special Service trim designed for detective and administrative uses.<ref>http://lowersouthampton.patch.com/articles/police-look-for-crown-victoria-replacement</ref> The Police Interceptor includes Ford's latest safety technology, like the Blind Spot Information System, rear view camera, reverse sensing system, and electronic stability control.\n\nIn 2015, Ford considered ending production of the Taurus in the United States.  However, the Police Interceptor Sedan was a major reason for continuing production.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bunkley|first=Nick|date=17 August 2015|title=The Taurus comeback story: Is it the end for ex-champ?|journal=[[Automotive News]]}}</ref>{{Clear}}\n\nIn 2018, [[Ford]] announced that it would be ending production of the [[Ford Taurus]] sedan on which the [[Ford Police Interceptor Sedan]] was based. In March of 2019, both the Taurus and Police Interceptor Sedan were discontinued. The Police Interceptor Sedan will be replaced by the second-generation, 2020 [[Ford Explorer]]-based [[Ford Police Interceptor Utility]], as well as the [[Ford Fusion]] [[Hybrid]] Police Responder, which was introduced for the 2019 [[model year]].\n\n=== Ford Fusion Hybrid Police Responder ===\n\nFor the 2019 [[model year]], a new \"Police Responder\" was introduced, based on the second-generation [[Ford Fusion]] [[Hybrid]]. The Fusion Hybrid Police Responder is the first pursuit-rated [[Hybrid Electric Vehicle]] (HEV).\n\n== Explorer (2012-Present) ==\n\n=== Ford Police Interceptor Utility ===\n{{Main|Ford Police Interceptor Utility}}\n[[File:Bellingham, WA Police- Ford Police Utility (17266247122).jpg|left|thumb|('''[[Bellingham Police Department]])''' The [[Ford Explorer|Ford Police Interceptor Utility]] was the second of two cars to replace the Crown Victoria. The Utility is based on the Ford Explorer.]]\nThe Utility was sold to police forces in 2012 and 2013, like the Taurus, although retail isn't available.\n\nThe Utility used the 3.7-liter V6 from the Ford Mustang, which produced {{Convert|305|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}. The car then featured the Ecoboost engine from the SHO in 2014, producing {{Convert|365|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.ford.com/news-center/press-releases-detail/hot-selling-ford-police-interceptor-utility-vehicle-now-offers-3|title=Ford Motor Company Official Global Corporate Homepage &#124; Ford.com|author=|date=2017-03-13|website=Corporate.ford.com|accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\nThe Utility comes with provisions for the fitment of emergency equipment such as guns, batons, tasers, radios, first aid kits, [[lightbar]]s and sirens. To free up interior space on the center console for equipment, the transmission is fitted with a column-mounted shifter. Other fleet-specific options are included as well. It also comes with an all-wheel drive powertrain as standard, and is also fitted with larger brake rotors, more advanced ABS and traction control systems, a more efficient cooling system and other standard police equipment.{{Clear}}\n\nIn 2019, for the 2020 [[model year]], the second-generation [[Ford Police Interceptor Utility]] was introduced with a new Rear Wheel Drive (RWD)-based platform, based on the sixth-generation [[Ford Explorer]] mid-size crossover [[SUV]]. It will replace the [[Ford Police Interceptor Sedan]] in [[Ford]]'s lineup as their \"purpose-built\" police vehicle.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Police vehicles]]\n", "name_user": "Squids and Chips", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFord Police Interceptor Sedan:disambiguate Ford Fusion and Hybrid to Ford Fusion Hybrid", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ford_Police_Interceptor_(variant)"}
{"title_page": "Bernard Rosenblum", "text_new": "[[Image:Photo-02.jpg|300px|thumb|upright=2|Bernard Rosenblum, Master Leather Craftsman]]\n\n'''Bernard Rosenblum''' (1927&ndash;2007) was a Master Craftsman Gilder and Art Restorer of the National Museums, the successor of the workshop [[Gainerie]] (word with no English translation:\"Leather Crafts Arts\") Bettenfeld. He was awarded the [[Political deportation and internment medal]] as well as Commander of the Order of Civic Education.\n\n==Early life==\nIn 1940 he entered the School of Fine Arts d'Angers. Then in 1941, due to the emergency laws of the Vichy government, he was prohibited from all studies. At the end of the Second World War, at the great liberation, he successively discovered the craft of upholstering in the workshops Vial, Veil and Reperman in which he was employed as a foreman, but he found that the saddle and leather work was just a technical and commercial transaction. A little disillusioned, he abandoned, for a time, the craft of [[leatherwork]]. {{citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\nHaving a strong attraction for the arts, especially painting and sculpture, he became a pupil of [[Alberto Giacometti]] and [[Emmanuel Mane-Katz]], during the golden era of [[Montparnasse]]. A family friend, who was an upholsterer, entrusted to him in 1960 the work of restoration of leather antiques, allowing him to make a living during this period in Montparnasse. He rediscovered leather and fell in love with its history. At that time he was to begin a research on leather and leather goods, in museums and libraries, which would never cease throughout his life.\n\nHe settled in 1963, as Upholsterer-Gilder, Rue de Reuilly in Paris, in the Rue du [[Faubourg Saint-Antoine]] district. He quickly created an excellent reputation. In 1965 Suzanne Bettenfeld proposed to him the succession of the prestigious Bettenfeld Studio, which then became the [[Studio Bettenfeld-Rosenblum]].  He also never stopped collecting the tools that are essential to his craft, [[bookbinding tools]], rollers and gilding plates. Including his participation with Roger Devauchelle to buy the workshop Gruel-Engelmann; he helped create one of the largest collections of postwar tools for gilding leather.\n\nHe became a preferred Master Restorer for the national museums and great decorators and antique dealers in France  and elsewhere; his clients included General [[Charles de Gaulle]], [[Jean Dutourd]], Claude L\u00e9vi-Strauss, King Hassan II of Morocco, the former court of Iran, and institutions such as the Army Museum, Rueil-Malmaison, Saumur, Versailles, the Paris Conservatoire.\n\nHe died suddenly in 2007. His son, David Rosenblum, reopened the studio in 2010.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n* Various journals and books in France and abroad from 1963 to 2007; ''Les M\u00e9tiers d'Art'', ''Marie-Claire-Japon'', ''Connaissances des Arts'', ''Art in America'', ''Time'', ''Maisons et D\u00e9corations''\u2026\n* ''Bernard Rosenblum \u2013 De l'Artisanat d'Art \u00e0 la Cr\u00e9ation Contemporaine'', documentaire de Dominique Mallegni, Institut des Hautes Etudes Cin\u00e9matographique, 1974 (Craft Art in Contemporary Design,''documentary byDominique Mallegni, Institute for Advanced Film Studies,1974).\n* ''Gainier Doreur d'Art de Tradition \u2013 l'atelier Bettenfeld Rosenblum'', th\u00e8se de Marie-Claire Bernard, [[Mus\u00e9e national des Arts et Traditions Populaires (France)|Mus\u00e9e national des Arts et Traditions populaires]], 1976 (Gainier ''Gilder Art Tradition \u2013 Workshop Bettenfeld Rosenblum \u00bb,  Marie-Claire Bernard, National Museum of Popular Arts and Traditions, 1976).\n* ''Trouvailles'', N\u00b031, October \u2013 November, Dossier Artisan d'Art Bernard Rosenblum Gainier de Tradition, 1981 (File Craftsman Art Bernard Rosenblum,1981).\n* ''Guide des Mus\u00e9es de France'', 1984 (Guide Museums of France, 1984).\n* ''L'Atelier Bettenfeld-Rosenblum'', reportage de France 3 T\u00e9l\u00e9vision (FR3), 1984 (The Studio Bettenfeld-Rosenblum, report France 3 TV).\n* ''La Collection Bettenfeld-Rosenblum'', 2000 Motifs et Ornements, Masahiro Miyamoto, \u00c9ditions Gakken,1987 (Collection-Bettenfeld''Rosenblum, 2000 Patterns andornaments, 1987).\n* ''Bookbinders' Finishing Tool Makers 1780-1965'', Tom Conroy, \u00c9ditions Oak Knoll Press, 2002.\n* ''Arts & M\u00e9tiers du Livre\", Les tr\u00e9sors de l'[[Atelier Bettenfeld-Rosenblum]], N\u00b0199, September\u2013October 1996, Page 49 \u00e0 51, Article de Raymond Faivre.\n* ''Arts & M\u00e9tiers du Livre\", Disparition de Bernard ROSENBLUM , N\u00b0260, Juin-Juillet 2007, Page 18.\n* ''Aladin'', D\u00e9c\u00e8s d'un Grand Artisan, N\u00b0226, 2007, Page 6.\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|en}} [http://www.dailymotion.com/video/xfblur_bernard-rosenblum-master-craftsman_creation/ Video Report of 1984 in dailymotion]\n* {{in lang|en}} {{https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NxKahXQwvwQ|Video Report of 1984}}\n* {{in lang|en}} Studio Bettenfeld-Rosenblum, Paris, France,  [http://www.leatherwork.abrparis.com/ Website Atelier Bettenfeld-Rosenblum]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosenblum, Bernard}}\n[[Category:20th-century French painters]]\n[[Category:French male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century French painters]]\n[[Category:French Jews]]\n[[Category:Modern artists]]\n[[Category:Modern sculptors]]\n[[Category:Artists from Paris]]\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century sculptors]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Photo-02.jpg|300px|thumb|upright=2|Bernard Rosenblum, Master Leather Craftsman]]\n\n'''Bernard Rosenblum''' (1927&ndash;2007) was a Master Craftsman Gilder and Art Restorer of the National Museums, the successor of the workshop [[Gainerie]] (word with no English translation:\"Leather Crafts Arts\") Bettenfeld. He was awarded the [[Political deportation and internment medal]] as well as Commander of the Order of Civic Education.\n\n==Early life==\nIn 1940 he entered the School of Fine Arts d'Angers. Then in 1941, due to the emergency laws of the Vichy government, he was prohibited from all studies. At the end of the Second World War, at the great liberation, he successively discovered the craft of upholstering in the workshops Vial, Veil and Reperman in which he was employed as a foreman, but he found that the saddle and leather work was just a technical and commercial transaction. A little disillusioned, he abandoned, for a time, the craft of [[leatherwork]]. {{citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\nHaving a strong attraction for the arts, especially painting and sculpture, he became a pupil of [[Alberto Giacometti]] and [[Emmanuel Mane-Katz]], during the golden era of [[Montparnasse]]. A family friend, who was an upholsterer, entrusted to him in 1960 the work of restoration of leather antiques, allowing him to make a living during this period in Montparnasse. He rediscovered leather and fell in love with its history. At that time he was to begin a research on leather and leather goods, in museums and libraries, which would never cease throughout his life.\n\nHe settled in 1963, as Upholsterer-Gilder, Rue de Reuilly in Paris, in the Rue du [[Faubourg Saint-Antoine]] district. He quickly created an excellent reputation. In 1965 Suzanne Bettenfeld proposed to him the succession of the prestigious Bettenfeld Studio, which then became the [[Studio Bettenfeld-Rosenblum]].  He also never stopped collecting the tools that are essential to his craft, [[bookbinding tools]], rollers and gilding plates. Including his participation with Roger Devauchelle to buy the workshop Gruel-Engelmann; he helped create one of the largest collections of postwar tools for gilding leather.\n\nHe became a preferred Master Restorer for the national museums and great decorators and antique dealers in France  and elsewhere; his clients included General [[Charles de Gaulle]], [[Jean Dutourd]], Claude L\u00e9vi-Strauss, King Hassan II of Morocco, the former court of Iran, and institutions such as the Army Museum, Rueil-Malmaison, Saumur, Versailles, the Paris Conservatoire.\n\nHe died suddenly in 2007. His son, David Rosenblum, reopened the studio in 2010.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n* Various journals and books in France and abroad from 1963 to 2007; ''Les M\u00e9tiers d'Art'', ''Marie-Claire-Japon'', ''Connaissances des Arts'', ''Art in America'', ''Time'', ''Maisons et D\u00e9corations''\u2026\n* ''Bernard Rosenblum \u2013 De l'Artisanat d'Art \u00e0 la Cr\u00e9ation Contemporaine'', documentaire de Dominique Mallegni, Institut des Hautes Etudes Cin\u00e9matographique, 1974 (Craft Art in Contemporary Design,''documentary byDominique Mallegni, Institute for Advanced Film Studies,1974).\n* ''Gainier Doreur d'Art de Tradition \u2013 l'atelier Bettenfeld Rosenblum'', th\u00e8se de Marie-Claire Bernard, [[Mus\u00e9e national des Arts et Traditions Populaires (France)|Mus\u00e9e national des Arts et Traditions populaires]], 1976 (Gainier ''Gilder Art Tradition \u2013 Workshop Bettenfeld Rosenblum \u00bb,  Marie-Claire Bernard, National Museum of Popular Arts and Traditions, 1976).\n* ''Trouvailles'', N\u00b031, October \u2013 November, Dossier Artisan d'Art Bernard Rosenblum Gainier de Tradition, 1981 (File Craftsman Art Bernard Rosenblum,1981).\n* ''Guide des Mus\u00e9es de France'', 1984 (Guide Museums of France, 1984).\n* ''L'Atelier Bettenfeld-Rosenblum'', reportage de France 3 T\u00e9l\u00e9vision (FR3), 1984 (The Studio Bettenfeld-Rosenblum, report France 3 TV).\n* ''La Collection Bettenfeld-Rosenblum'', 2000 Motifs et Ornements, Masahiro Miyamoto, \u00c9ditions Gakken,1987 (Collection-Bettenfeld''Rosenblum, 2000 Patterns andornaments, 1987).\n* ''Bookbinders' Finishing Tool Makers 1780-1965'', Tom Conroy, \u00c9ditions Oak Knoll Press, 2002.\n* ''Arts & M\u00e9tiers du Livre\", Les tr\u00e9sors de l'[[Atelier Bettenfeld-Rosenblum]], N\u00b0199, September\u2013October 1996, Page 49 \u00e0 51, Article de Raymond Faivre.\n* ''Arts & M\u00e9tiers du Livre\", Disparition de Bernard ROSENBLUM , N\u00b0260, Juin-Juillet 2007, Page 18.\n* ''Aladin'', D\u00e9c\u00e8s d'un Grand Artisan, N\u00b0226, 2007, Page 6.\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|en}} [http://www.dailymotion.com/video/xfblur_bernard-rosenblum-master-craftsman_creation/ Video Report of 1984 in dailymotion]\n* {{in lang|en}} {{youtube|TeY7kB2rDiE|Video Report of 1984}}\n* {{in lang|en}} Studio Bettenfeld-Rosenblum, Paris, France,  [http://www.leatherwork.abrparis.com/ Website Atelier Bettenfeld-Rosenblum]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosenblum, Bernard}}\n[[Category:20th-century French painters]]\n[[Category:French male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century French painters]]\n[[Category:French Jews]]\n[[Category:Modern artists]]\n[[Category:Modern sculptors]]\n[[Category:Artists from Paris]]\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century sculptors]]\n", "name_user": "Amorial1815", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Rosenblum"}
{"title_page": "Judy Sheindlin", "text_new": "{{short description|American lawyer, judge, television personality, and author}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = bob \nSheindlin\n| image              = Judge Judy Sheindlin VF 2012 Shankbone.JPG\n| caption            = Sheindlin at the 2012 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]\n| birth_name         = Judith Susan Blum\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1942|10|21}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = {{unbulleted list|[[American University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]) | [[New York Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Lawyer|judge|television personality|author|[[arbitrator]]}}\n| years_active       = {{unbulleted list | 1965\u20131982 (attorney) | 1982\u20131996 (judge) | 1996\u2013present (television personality)}}\n| known_for          = ''[[Judge Judy]]''\n| children           = 2\n| spouse             = Ronald Levy (m. 1964\u20131976)<br />[[Jerry Sheindlin]] (m. 1977\u20131990; m. 1991)\n| net_worth          = $500 million<ref>{{Cite web|last= Singer |first=Jenny  |authorlink=   |title=These Are America's Richest Self-Made Jewish Women |publisher=[[Jewish Daily Forward]]|date=July 12, 2018 |url=https://forward.com/schmooze/405267/these-are-americas-richest-self-made-jewish-women/  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Judith Susan Sheindlin''' (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' '''Blum'''; born October 21, 1942),<ref name=\"bio\" /> known professionally as '''Judge Judy''', is an American [[Prosecutor|prosecution lawyer]], former [[Manhattan]] family court judge, television personality, and author. Since September 1996, Sheindlin has presided over her own successful four-time [[Daytime Emmy Award]]\u2013winning [[court show#Arbitration=-based reality court show|arbitration-based court show series]], ''[[Judge Judy]]'', produced by [[CBS Television Distribution]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.biography.com/personality/judge-judy | website= [[Biography.com]] |accessdate=February 6, 2020 |publisher=Biography, A&E Television Networks |title=Judge Judy Biography - Judge, Author, Reality Television Star (1942\u2013)}}</ref> She stated on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' she would finish up with the series after the conclusion of the 2020/2021 season, which would mark a 25 year run, as she would be launching a new series titled ''Judy Justice'', which would be of a similar format.<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/judge-judy-sheindlin-judy-justice-scott-koondel-1203520868/|title=Judge Judy Sets Sights on Streaming, Cable Arena for Next Chapter with 'Judy Justice'}}</ref>\n\nSheindlin passed the New York state [[bar examination]] in 1965 and became a [[prosecutor]] in the [[family court]] system. In 1982 [[Mayor of New York|New York City Mayor]] [[Ed Koch]] appointed her as a judge, first in criminal court, then later as Manhattan's supervising family court judge in 1986.\n\nSheindlin is the longest-serving judge or arbitrator in courtroom-themed programming history, a distinction that earned Sheindlin a place in the ''[[Guinness World Records]]''.<ref name=\"etonline\">{{cite web |url=http://www.etonline.com/media/video/judge_judy_sets_a_guinness_world_record-171890/ |title=Judge Judy Sets a Guinness World Record! |publisher=Etonline.com}}</ref> She has additionally received a [[Lifetime Achievement Emmy]] for her work; during the 2019 awards ceremony, [[comedienne]] [[Amy Poehler]] referred to Sheindlin as \"the Jewish mother we all want\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/tv-movies/a27372453/judge-judy-amy-poehler-lifetime-achievement-award-daytime-emmys/|title=Amy Poehler Fan Girls Over Judge Judy at the Daytime Emmy Awards|date=May 6, 2019|first=Emma|last=Dibdin|accessdate=April 8, 2020|publisher=[[OprahMag.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSheindlin was born Judith Susan Blum in the [[Brooklyn]] [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of [[New York City]], to a [[Jewish]] family, from Germany, Russia, and Ukraine.<ref name=CTRL-F-Jewish-passsge>{{cite web|url=https://forward.com/sisterhood/210866/life-love-and-the-proverbs-of-judge-judy/|title=Life, Love and the Proverbs of Judge Judy|website=[[The Forward]]|access-date=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=CTRL-F-Jewish-subheader>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/International/Order-in-her-court-Judge-Judith-Judy-Sheindlin-504679|title=#39 Judy Sheindlin - Order in her court - International news |website=[[Jerusalem Post]] |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=Facts>{{cite news |url=http://www.lawfuel.com/blog/judge-judy/|title=24 Facts and Things You Never Knew About Judge Judy|access-date=August 5, 2018|work=LawFuel|date=January 20, 2016|location=New Zealand}}</ref> She described her father as \"the greatest thing since sliced bread\" and her mother as \"a meat and potatoes kind of gal.\"<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/09/realitytv.television|title=Judy, madly, deeply|access-date=December 14, 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Weldon|first=Fay|author-link=Fay Weldon|date=October 9, 2008|location=London}}</ref>\n\nSheindlin attended [[James Madison High School (Brooklyn)|James Madison High School]] in Brooklyn before going on to [[American University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], where she graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree, majoring in government. She finished her law school education at [[New York Law School]], where she earned her [[Juris Doctor]] degree in 1965.<ref name=\"judy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.judgejudy.com/bios|title=Judge Judith Sheindlin: Presiding Judge|access-date=November 19, 2011|publisher=[[CBS Television Distribution]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSheindlin passed the New York state [[bar examination]] in 1965, the same year as her graduation, and was hired as a [[corporate lawyer]] for a cosmetics firm.<ref name=\"bio\" /> Within two years she became dissatisfied with her job and left to raise her two children. She was made aware of a position in the New York court system as a prosecutor in the family courts in 1972.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In her role as a lawyer, Sheindlin prosecuted child abuse cases, domestic violence and juvenile crime.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nBy 1982, Sheindlin's \"no-nonsense\" attitude inspired New York Mayor [[Ed Koch]] to appoint her as a criminal court judge.<ref name=\"bio\" /> Four years later, she was promoted to supervising judge in the family court's Manhattan division.<ref name=\"bio\" /> She earned a reputation as a \"tough\" judge (though she has disagreed with the labels \"tough\" and \"harsh\"),<ref name=\"wdrb.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/19965962/judge-judy-explains-how-she-can-tell-someone-is-lying |title=Judge Judy explains how she can tell someone is lying&nbsp;\u2013 WDRB 41 Louisville&nbsp;\u2013 News, Weather, Sports Community |website=Wdrb.com |accessdate=December 21, 2012}}</ref> known for her fast decision-making and acerbic wit.<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n\nIn February 1993, Sheindlin's outspoken reputation made her the subject of a ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' article,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1993-02-14/news/vw-307_1_family-court |title=Law and Disorder |first=Josh |last=Getlin |work=Los Angeles Times |date=February 14, 1993}}</ref> profiling her as a woman determined to make the court system work for the common good.<ref name=\"bio\" /> She subsequently was featured in a segment on CBS's ''[[60 Minutes]]'' that brought her national recognition.<ref name=\"bio\" /> This led to her first book, ''Don't Pee on My Leg and Tell Me It's Raining'', published in 1996. She retired as a family court judge that same year after having heard more than 20,000 cases.<ref name=\"bio\" /> \n\n===''Judge Judy'' ===\n{{Main|Judge Judy}}\n\n[[File:Judge Judy next to painting.jpg|thumb|right|Judge Judy stands next to a portrait of herself (2005)]]\n\nAfter the ''60 Minutes'' special on her family court career in 1993 and authoring her first book shortly thereafter (''Don't Pee on My Leg and Tell Me It's Raining''), Sheindlin was approached about starring in a new [[reality television#Reality court shows|reality]] courtroom series, featuring \"real cases with real rulings.\"<ref name=\"judy\" /> She accepted the offer, and her ongoing [[Television syndication|syndicated]] court show, ''Judge Judy'', debuted on September 16, 1996.<ref name=\"Stun Creative\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stuncreative.com/buster/cbs-judge-judy-20th-anniversary/|title=CBS JUDGE JUDY 20TH ANNIVERSARY |publisher=Stun Creative |date= |accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref> The court show's present 24th season commenced on September 9, 2019. \n\nSince its debut, ''Judge Judy'' has remained the No. 1 rated court show<ref name=\"nydn\" /> and regularly draws approximately 9 to 10 million viewers daily.<ref name=\"ppg\">{{cite news |work=The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |accessdate=December 24, 2008 |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08359/937221-42.stm |title=There's no justice like show justice |author=Leroux, Charles |date=December 24, 2008}}</ref> During the 2009\u201310 television season, ''Judge Judy'' became the first TV series in nearly a decade to attract more daytime viewers than ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Highfill |first=Samantha |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/05/02/judge-judy-renewed-2015/ |title='Judge Judy' renewed through 2015 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> Since then, it has been the highest rated show in all of daytime television.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2010/09/20/judge-judy-kicks-off-15th-season-as-the-number-1-daytime-show-in-syndication-570011/20100920cbs03/ |title=Ratings&nbsp;\u2013 \"Judge Judy\" Kicks Off 15th Season as the No. 1 Daytime Show in Syndication |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |date=September 16, 1996 |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 2015, [[CBS Television Distribution]] and Judge Sheindlin extended their contract for another four seasons, adding to her current contract (which was set to expire after the 2016\u201317 season), meaning it will be on the air until at least the 2020\u201321 season.<ref>[https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/judge-judy-extends-big-bucks-contract-with-cbs-through-2020-1201444365/ \"'Judge Judy' Extends Big Bucks Contract With CBS Through 2020\"] ''Variety'', March 2, 2015</ref> At that point, as Judge Sheindlin revealed in a March 2020 appearance on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'', the series will conclude.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ramos |first=Dino-Ray |title=\u2018Judge Judy\u2019 Wraps After 25 Seasons, Sheindlin To Return With \u2018Judy Justice\u2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/judge-judy-ends-25-seasons-judy-sheindlin-judy-justice-ellen-degeneres-show-1202871873/ |website=Deadline |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAuthor [[Brendan I. Koerner]] has commented on the popularity of ''Judge Judy'':\n\n<blockquote>Court-show viewers don't seem to want moral conundrums or technical wrinkles. They love Sheindlin's show because she offers them a fantasy of how they'd like the justice system to operate\u2014swiftly, and without procedural mishaps or uppity lawyers. They get to see wrongdoers publicly humiliated by a strong authority figure. There is no uncertainty after Sheindlin renders her verdict and bounds off the bench, and there certainly are no lengthy appeals.<ref name=\"slate\">{{cite news |url=http://slate.com/id/2118556/ |title=Judge Judy |author=Koerner, Brendan I |work=Slate |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |date=May 27, 2005}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nA 2013 ''[[Reader's Digest]]'' poll supported Koerner's statements, revealing that [[Americans]] trusted Judge Judy more than all nine justices of the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]].<ref name=\"sullivan1\">{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Sean |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2013/05/17/jimmy-kimmel-asks-judge-judy-for-the-supreme-court-video/ |title=Jimmy Kimmel asks: Judge Judy for the Supreme Court? (VIDEO) |work=The Washington Post |date=February 24, 2011 |accessdate=May 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe program has integrated itself into American [[popular culture]].<ref name=\"judy\" /> In 2003, [[VH1]] named Sheindlin one of the \"200 Greatest Pop Culture Icons.\"<ref name=\"judgejudy2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.judgejudy.com/bios |title=Judge Judy Bio |website=Judgejudy.com |accessdate=May 19, 2013}}</ref> References to Sheindlin\u2014typically as \"Judge Judy\", though often [[satire|satirical]]\u2014have appeared in multitudes of television programs and other media, including ABC's ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'';<ref name=\"sullivan1\" /> Fox's ''[[The Simpsons]]'' as Judge Constance Harm (voiced by [[Jane Kaczmarek]]); NBC's ''[[Will & Grace]]''; UPN/The CW's ''[[America's Next Top Model]]''; NBC's ''[[The Weakest Link]]''; ABC's ''[[The Practice]]''; the ''[[Academy Awards]]''; the book ''America: A Citizen's Guide to Democracy Inaction'' by [[Jon Stewart]];<ref name=\"judy\" /> a skit by [[Vicki Lawrence]] portraying [[Thelma Harper]]/[[Mama's Family|Mama]] on ''\"[[Betty White]]'s 2nd Annual 90th Birthday\"'' celebration,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/movies-specials-more/video/categories/betty-whites-second-annual-90th-birthday-party/ |title=Video Gallery &#124; Movies & Specials &#124; All Videos: Newest |publisher=NBC |accessdate=March 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021100858/http://www.nbc.com/movies-specials-more/video/categories/betty-whites-second-annual-90th-birthday-party/ |archivedate=October 21, 2013 }}</ref> drag queen [[Bianca Del Rio]] portraying Judge Judy on ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'', etc.\n\nSheindlin has been parodied on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', ''[[The Simpsons]]'' as Judge Constance Harm, and ''[[The Amanda Show]]'' as Judge Trudy.\n\nThe ''Judge Judy'' courtroom series has earned Sheindlin numerous awards and honors, including a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in February 2006;<ref>{{cite web |website=Hollywood.com |accessdate=December 24, 2008 |url=http://www.hollywood.com/photo_gallery/Judge_Judy_Sheindlin_Hollywood_Walk_of_Fame_Ceremony/3525341# |title=Judge Judy Sheindlin Hollywood Walk of Fame Ceremony Photo Gallery}}</ref> induction into ''[[Broadcasting & Cable]]''{{'}}s [[Hall of Fame]] in October 2012;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/488448-The_Battle_to_Survive_at_the_Top.php |title=The Battle to 'Survive' at the Top&nbsp;\u2013 2012-08-13 04:01:00 &#124; Broadcasting & Cable |website=Broadcastingcable.com |accessdate=December 13, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203074626/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/488448-The_Battle_to_Survive_at_the_Top.php |archivedate=December 3, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/13/judge-judy-katie-couric_n_2123114.html |title=Judge Judy on Future: 'Every Stage In Your Life Has A New Adventure' |work=The Huffington Post |date=November 13, 2012 |accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref> being awarded [[vice president|vice presidency]] of the [[University College Dublin Law Society|UCD Law Society]] in April 2013;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/judge-judy-honoured-by-ucd-society-1.1355090 |title=Judge Judy honoured by UCD society&nbsp;\u2013 Irish News, World News & More &#124; The Irish Times&nbsp;\u2013 Tue, April 09, 2013 |work=The Irish Times |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> being presented with the Gracie Allen Tribute Award from the [[Alliance for Women in Media]];<ref name=\"judgejudy2\" /> being awarded the Mary Pickford Award by the Hollywood Chamber Community Foundation at the 2014 Heroes of Hollywood;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/contact-us/community/Heroes-of-Hollywood--266830821.html |title=Heroes of Hollywood Honors Judge Judy Sheindlin |website=[[NBC Southern California]] |date=July 11, 2014 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> etc.\n\nOne award Sheindlin had difficulty winning was a [[Daytime Emmy Award]]. By 2011, her program had been nominated 14 consecutive years without winning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/nightlinedailyline/2010/05/toughtalking-oprah-competititor-judge-judy.html |title=Allumination Filmworks Is Proud to Release the First DVD From Everyone's Favorite No\u2013Nonsense Judge&nbsp;\u2013 Judge Judy Sheindlin |website=Sys-con.com |accessdate=July 22, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontheredcarpet.com/Daytime-Emmys-2011:-Full-list-of-nominees/8125012 |title=Daytime Emmys 2011 nominations: See full list&nbsp;\u2013 06/17/2011 &#124; Entertainment News from |website=OnTheRedCarpet.com |accessdate=December 13, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819003504/http://www.ontheredcarpet.com/Daytime-Emmys-2011:-Full-list-of-nominees/8125012 |archive-date=August 19, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In mid-2012, an article from the ''[[New York Post]]'' reported that ''Judge Judy'' was snubbed by the award show by [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Legal/Courtroom Program|not even being nominated that year]] despite being the highest-rated court show.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/tv/emmys_snub_judge_judy_view_ish_girls_rYCz3u5L1qcxeuE5kW6LpN |work=[[New York Post]] |title=Emmys snub Judge Judy, 'View'ish girls |date=May 10, 2012}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' (ET) on May 3, 2013, Sheindlin said, \"I have my walls full of Daytime Emmy Award nominations.\" When ET's interviewer asked Sheindlin if she thought she would ever win the award, she replied:\n\n{{quote|I don't know. You know, somehow it would sort of break the spell. The show has been such a tremendous success that I'm almost afraid to think about winning\u2014because so many of those shows that did win are no longer with us. So I say to myself 'you want the Emmy or you want a job? (laughing) Which one do you want?'<ref name=\"etonline1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/133630_Judge_Judy_on_How_Celebrities_Are_Treated_in_the_Justice_System/ |title=Judge Judy on Celebrities and the Justice System |website=ETonline.com |date=April 29, 2013 |accessdate=May 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129031501/http://www.etonline.com/news/133630_Judge_Judy_on_How_Celebrities_Are_Treated_in_the_Justice_System/ |archivedate=January 29, 2014 }}</ref>}}\n\nOn June 14, 2013, ''[[Judge Judy]]'' won its first Daytime Emmy for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Legal/Courtroom Program|Outstanding Legal/Courtroom Program]], having received its 15th nomination.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enstarz.com/articles/19832/20130615/daytime-emmy-awards-2013-ellen-degeneres-show-sesame-street-judge.htm |title=Daytime Emmy Awards 2013: 'The Ellen DeGeneres Show', 'Sesame Street', 'Judge Judy' Win Awards: TV |website=Enstarz.com |date=October 22, 2012 |accessdate=June 17, 2013}}</ref> The program won again in 2016 and 2017. Sheindlin's status as longest-serving judge or arbitrator in courtroom-themed programming history rewarded her a place in the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' on September 14, 2015, as part of her court show's 20th-anniversary celebration.<ref name=\"etonline\"/>\n\n==== Longevity and retirement plans ====\nThe only court shows that outnumber ''Judge Judy''{{'}}s seasons are ''[[The People's Court]]'' and ''[[Divorce Court]]''\u2014both of which have suffered cancellation(s) and gone through multiple judges or arbitrators.\n\nOn March 30, 2011, Sheindlin was admitted to the hospital after she fainted on the set of her show while handling a case. She was released the next day, and it was later learned that she suffered a [[Transient ischemic attack|mini-stroke]].<ref>https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2011/05/04/judge-judy-says-she-thinks-she-suffered-a-mini-stroke/</ref> Regarding her retirement, Sheindlin has stated that it is up to her viewers and when they tire of watching the program, which she believes will inevitably happen one day. As of the present, however, Sheindlin has stated that fans still seem to be interested and taking something out of the court show.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/19965962/judge-judy-explains-how-she-can-tell-someone-is-lying |title=Judge Judy explains how she can tell someone is lying&nbsp;\u2013 WDRB 41 Louisville&nbsp;\u2013 News, Weather, Sports Community |website=Wdrb.com |accessdate=May 18, 2013}}</ref> Sheindlin admits the court show is \"seductive\" and hard to give up. Sheindlin said, \"I'm not tired. I still feel engaged by what I do, and I still have people who like to watch it.\"<ref name=\"nydn\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2008/01/29/2008-01-29_judge_judy_will_keep_warming_bench.html |title=Judge Judy will keep warming bench |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |date=January 29, 2008 |work=The New York Daily News |author=Huff, Richard}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Sheindlin announced that the 2020-21 season of the show will be the last, after 25 years. A new program, entitled \"Judy Justice\" is set to air in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/judge-judy-end-after-25-years-t174930|title=Judge Judy to end her show after 25 years \u2014 but she isn't leaving TV just yet|website=TODAY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\n====Salary ====\nIn 2005, Sheindlin's salary was US$15 million per year.<ref name=\"slate\" /> Her [[net worth]] at the beginning of 2007 was $95 million, and she ranked #13 on the ''[[Forbes]]'' top 20 richest women in entertainment.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Pictures: The Richest 20 Women in Entertainment: Judith \"Judge Judy\" Sheindlin |url=https://www.forbes.com/2007/01/17/richest-women-entertainment-tech-media-cz_lg_richwomen07_0118womenstars_slide_14.html |author=Goldman, Lea and Kiri Blakeley |work=Forbes |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |date=January 18, 2008}}</ref> In July 2010 when Sheindlin's contract was renewed, her salary increased to $45 million per year. It was later reported in October 2013 that Sheindlin is the highest-paid TV star, earning $47 million per year for ''Judge Judy'', which translates into just over $900,000 per workday (she works 52 days per year).<ref name=\"parade1\">{{cite web |author=Lindsay Lowe |url=http://www.parade.com/217711/linzlowe/happy-birthday-judge-judy-5-things-you-didnt-know-about-judy-sheindlin/ |title=Happy Birthday, Judge Judy! 5 Things You Didn't Know About Judy Sheindlin |website=Parade.com |date=March 14, 2012 |accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref>  According to Forbes, Sheindlin earned $147 million, pretax, in 2017.<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite web |author=Madeline Berg |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maddieberg/2018/11/26/the-worlds-highest-paid-tv-hosts-2018-judge-judy-presides-with-147-million/#aaf8fdb48d67/ |title=The World's Highest-Paid TV Hosts 2018: Judge Judy Presides With $147 Million |website=Forbes.com |date=November 26, 2018 |accessdate=November 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Other media appearances ===\nSince the success of Sheindlin's courtroom series, she has been interviewed on [[talk show|talk]] and [[news broadcasting|cable news]] broadcasts over the course of her career. These talk and cable news programs include ''Entertainment Tonight'', ''[[The Wendy Williams Show]]'',<ref name=\"wchstv\" /> ''[[Katie (talk show)|Katie]]'' (numerous appearances),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.katiecouric.com/on-the-show/2012/11/12/daytime-star-judge-judy/ |title=Judge Judy Like You've Never Seen Her Before&nbsp;\u2013 Katie Couric |website=Katiecouric.com |date=November 12, 2012 |accessdate=March 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121224094505/http://www.katiecouric.com/on-the-show/2012/11/12/daytime-star-judge-judy/ |archivedate=December 24, 2012 }}</ref> ''[[Larry King Live]]'' (numerous appearances),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://larrykinglive.blogs.cnn.com/category/judge-judy/ |title=Judge Judy&nbsp;\u2013 Larry King Live&nbsp;\u2013 CNN.com Blogs |publisher=CNN |date=February 17, 2010 |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'' (numerous appearances),<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=http://theview.abc.go.com/category/tags/judge-judy |title=The View &#124; Judge Judy |publisher=American Broadcasting Company |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Donny & Marie (1998 TV series)|Donny & Marie]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvclip.biz/video/KgaprbQLiAE/donny-marie-with-judge-judy.html |title=Donny & Marie With Judge Judy |website=Tvclip.biz |date=May 18, 2010 |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> ''[[The Talk (TV series)|The Talk]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author=Cathy |url=http://haveuheard.net/2010/10/the-talk-upcoming-guests-including-hilary-swank-and-judge-judy/ |title='The Talk' Upcoming Guests Including Hilary Swank and Judge Judy &#124; HaveUHeardHaveUHeard |website=Haveuheard.net |date=October 25, 2010 |accessdate=March 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314185713/http://haveuheard.net/2010/10/the-talk-upcoming-guests-including-hilary-swank-and-judge-judy/ |archivedate=March 14, 2013 }}</ref> ''[[The Tonight Show]]'', ''[[Dateline NBC]]'', ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'', etc.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbspressexpress.com/cbs-television-distribution/shows/judge-judy/about |title=Press Express &#124; Not Available |website=Cbspressexpress.com |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> On October 17, 1998, Sheindlin made a surprise guest appearance on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', comedically interrupting one of [[Cheri Oteri]]'s regular [[parody|parodies]] of her presiding on ''Judge Judy.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snltranscripts.jt.org/98/98cjudy.phtml |title=SNL Transcripts: Lucy Lawless: 10/17/98: Judge Judy |website=Snltranscripts.jt.org |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> Also as a result of her ''Judge Judy'' show stardom, she served as a judge for the [[Miss America 1999|1999 Miss America pageant]].<ref name=\"wchstv\">{{cite news|url=http://www.wchstv.com/synd_prog/judy/ |accessdate=December 24, 2008 |year=2000 |title=Judge Judy |publisher=WCHS-TV8 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720040832/http://wchstv.com/synd_prog/judy/ |archivedate=July 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nEarly on in her celebrity on February 21, 2000, the ''[[Biography (TV series)|Biography]]'' program aired a documentary film on Sheindlin, \"Judge Judy: Sitting in Judgment\" (later released on [[home video]]). This 60-minute documentary captured Sheindlin's entire life story (dating back to her childhood), legal career, authoring career, entertainment career, etc. The special also featured input from those closest to Sheindlin and those who knew her best.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/detail/tv-show.aspx?tvobjectid=191411&more=ucepisodelist&episodeid=2321878 |title=Biography Episode Guide 2000&nbsp;\u2013 Judge Judy: Sitting in Judgement |work=TV Guide |accessdate=March 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.nytimes.com/show/52248/Judge-Judy-Sitting-in-Judgment/overview |title=Judge Judy: Sitting in Judgment |accessdate=March 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415172748/http://tv.nytimes.com/show/52248/Judge-Judy-Sitting-in-Judgment/overview |archivedate=April 15, 2014 }}</ref> On December 23, 2008, Sheindlin shared about her life on ''[[Shatner's Raw Nerve]]'', in which she was interviewed by [[William Shatner]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/shatners-raw-nerve-2008/episode-6-season-1/judge-judy/296013 |title=Shatner's Raw Nerve Episode Guide 2008 Season 1&nbsp;\u2013 Judge Judy, Episode 6 |work=TV Guide |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> A year later in December 2009, Sheindlin again told the story of her life, legal career, authoring career, and entertainment courtroom career from an updated perspective in a two-hour interview for ''[[Archive of American Television]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/judith-sheindlin |title=Judith Sheindlin Interview |website=EmmyTVLegends.org |accessdate=March 20, 2013}}</ref> In a free-wheeling 60-minute interview conducted by [[Katie Couric]] on September 17, 2013, for the [[92nd Street Y]], Sheindlin elaborated on previously-undisclosed fun facts of her life story and long career in the family court.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_7p8LWbp8qM |title=Judge Judy with Katie Couric |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=November 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.92y.org/Event/Judge-Judy.aspx |title=Judge Judy with Katie Couric&nbsp;\u2013 92nd Street Y&nbsp;\u2013 New York, NY |website=92y.org |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=November 16, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918060653/http://www.92y.org/Event/Judge-Judy.aspx |archivedate=September 18, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nAs confirmed in January 2014, a new court show conceived by Sheindlin titled ''[[Hot Bench]]'' debuted on September 15, 2014. The courtroom series features a panel of three judges debating and deciding on cases brought to their TV courtroom. Stated Sheindlin, \"When my husband Jerry and I were in [[Ireland]] recently, we visited the courts and watched a three-judge bench, which I found both fascinating and compelling. I immediately thought what a terrific and unique idea for a television program that brings the court genre to the next level. We have assembled three individuals with extremely varied backgrounds to serve as the judges. They are smart and talented, with terrific instincts and great chemistry, and are sure to create a hot bench.\" The panel of judges consists of [[New York State Supreme Court]] judge [[Patricia DiMango]] and Los Angeles attorneys Tanya Acker and Larry Bakman (Bakman has since been replaced on ''Hot Bench'' by Michael Corriero). As with ''Judge Judy'', ''Hot Bench'' is executive-produced by Randy Douthit and produced by CBS Television Distribution.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/judge-judy-sheindlin-to-launch-new-court-show-in-the-fall-1201068123/ |title=CBS To Launch New Courtshow From Judge Judy in Fall |work=Variety |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/judge-judy-created-hot-bench-premiere-fall-features-trio-of-judges |title=Judge Judy-Created 'Hot Bench' to Premiere in the Fall |publisher=TheWrap |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> Sheindlin originally desired the title of her personal courtroom series to be ''Hot Bench'' before producers ultimately settled on ''Judge Judy''.<ref name=\"cbsnews1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/2100-500164_162-551386.h |title=Judge Judy |publisher=CBS News |date=February 11, 2009 |accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/shows/judge-judy |title=Judge Judy &#124; Archive of American Television |website=Emmytvlegends.org |accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/9512194705/big-ticket-sets-hot-bench |title=Big Ticket sets 'Hot Bench'&nbsp;\u2013 Tags: HOT Bench With Judge Judy Sheindlin (TV program) BIG Ticket Television (Company) |website=Connection.ebscohost.com |accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn August 31, 2016, it was reported that CBS has a scripted, semi-[[autobiography|autobiographical]] [[drama (film and television)|drama series]] in the works based on the life of Sheindlin. The program title will be ''Her Honor'' (which was a proposed title for Sheindlin's court show along with ''Hot Bench''). The show has been described as following the youngest judge in New York who, while proficient at handling family court cases, has a personal life that needs work. Executive producers of the program include Sheindlin herself, Chernuchin, Arnold Kopelson and Anne Kopelson. Chernuchin was a writer for the [[legal drama]] series ''[[Law & Order (franchise)|Law & Order]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/judge-judy-cbs-drama-series-her-honor-1201848403/ |title=Judge Judy Developing Scripted Series at CBS Based on Her Life (EXCLUSIVE) |publisher=Variety.com |accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2016/09/01/judge-judy-sheindlin-drama-pilot-her-honor-cbs/ |title=CBS, Judge Judy Team for Autobiographical Drama Series |publisher=Tvline.com |accessdate=September 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/judge-judy-drama-cbs-her-honor/ |title=CBS Is Developing an Autobiographical Drama About Judge Judy |publisher=Tvguide.com |accessdate=September 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Sheindlin created a game show called ''[[IWitness]]'' that debuted on July 10 and ran for 6 weeks. The game show puts the contestant's observational skills to the test, requiring them to view video clips and recall what they have witnessed faster than their competitors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.longislandpress.com/2017/07/11/iwitness-new-game-show-from-judge-judy-debuts/ |title=iWitness: New Game Show from Judge Judy Debuts |publisher=Long Island Press |accessdate=September 9, 2017}}</ref> On September 17, 2017, Sheindlin appeared on the series premiere of Fox News Channel's ''Objectified'' hosted by [[Harvey Levin]]. The program's first episode took an inside look at Sheindlin's life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2017/09/06/fox-news-channels-objectified-series-hosted-by-harvey-levin-to-premiere-featuring-judge-judy.html |title=Fox News Channel's Objectified Series Hosted By Harvey Levin, to premiere featuring Judge Judy |accessdate=September 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[National Enquirer]]'' issued a formal apology in the September 2017 edition of their magazine for false statements, [[defamatory|defaming]] Sheindlin as having cheated on her husband and suffering from [[Alzheimer's Disease]] along with [[brain damage]]. In addition, they apologized to her daughter Nicole Sheindlin for defaming her as having a jail record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalenquirer.com/celebrity/apology-regarding-judge-judy-nicole-sheindlin/ |title=Apology Regarding Judge Judy And Nicole Sheindlin |publisher=National Enquirer |last= Taylor |first=J.R. |date=September 20, 2017 |accessdate=January 28, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nSheindlin and her program appeared on a November 26, 2017 broadcast of ''[[Curb Your Enthusiasm]]'', presiding over a [[sketch comedy]] court case with [[Larry David]] as the plaintiff. The pseudo-Judge Judy case took the appearance of an actual case from Sheindlin's program, taking place from the show's courtroom set with trademarked voice-over briefs, theme music and audience response.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2017/11/27/judge-judy-makes-hilarious-guest-appearance-on-curb-your-enthusiasm.html |title=judge judy makes hilarious guest appearance on 'Curb Your Enthusiasm' |publisher=Foxnews.com |date=November 27, 2017 |accessdate=November 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Sheindlin appeared as a guest on ''[[Norm Macdonald Has a Show]]'' on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eponymousreview.com/3998/norm-macdonald-netflix-show-chevy-chase-m-night-shyamalan/|title=Norm Macdonald's Netflix show to guest Chevy Chase, Judge Judy, M. Night Shyamalan {{!}} Eponymous Review|website=www.eponymousreview.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Writing ===\nSheindlin has authored seven books. In 1995, Judge Sheindlin published her first book, ''Don't Pee On My Leg and Tell Me It's Raining'', in which she offers her insight into how and why the family court fails in its mission to impact shattered families. ''Beauty Fades, Dumb Is Forever'', her second book, was published in January 1999. Her first children's book entitled, ''Win or Lose By How You Choose'' was published in 2000, followed by ''You Can't Judge A Book By Its Cover'' the next year. Sheindlin's third book for adults, ''Keep It Simple, Stupid: You're Smarter Than You Look'', also on the ''New York Times'' best seller list, published in 2000, shares her wisdom and opinions on solving family issues.<ref name=\"judgejudy.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.judgejudy.com/bios|title=Judge Judy - Bio|website=Judge Judy|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> One of her more recent books, which hit shelves on April 25, 2013, was inspired by one of her advisory catch phrases encouraging romantic partners to be judicious with regards to [[domestic partnership]]s.<ref name=\"nypost1\">{{cite news |last=Adams |first=Cindy |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/pagesix/cindy_adams/judge_judy_on_domestic_love_Q6UBVoMDodIdshBxpFJs1H |title=Judge Judy's fifth book, \"What Would Judy Say? A Grown-Up Guide To Living Together With Benefits,\" is upon us |work=New York Post |date=April 25, 2013 |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> In September 2014, Sheindlin celebrated the opening of her 19th season by giving out her latest book, ''What Would Judy Say: Be the Hero of Your Own Story'', for free.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Non-media projects and community work===\nSheindlin, along with her stepdaughter Nicole Sheindlin, is the creator, director, and spokesperson for an alliance designed to empower women, entitled \"Her Honor Mentoring\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.herhonor.org |title=herhonor Mentoring |publisher=Her Honor Mentoring |accessdate=November 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.herhonor.org/about-us/history|title=Her Honor Mentoring - Mission + History|website=www.herhonor.org|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Sheindlin funded a space for public debate at the [[University of Southern California]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2017/09/13/judge-judy-usc-debate-forum/ |title=Judge Judy Funds Debate Forum At USC |publisher=CBSLos Angeles |accessdate=January 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1964, Blum married Ronald Levy, who later became a [[prosecutor]] in [[juvenile court]]. They moved to New York and had two children, Jamie and Adam,<ref name=\"bio\" /> and divorced in 1976 after 12 years of marriage.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nIn 1977, she married Judge [[Jerry Sheindlin]], who was an arbitrator on ''[[The People's Court]]'' from 1999 to 2001.<ref name=\"bio\" /> They divorced in 1990, partially as a result of the stress and struggles that Judy endured after her father's death that same year.<ref name=\"bio\" /> They remarried a year later. She has three stepchildren with Sheindlin: Gregory, Jonathan and Nicole, and 13 grandchildren.<ref name=\"bio\" /> Jonathan is a [[Eye surgery#Vitreo-retinal surgery|retinal surgeon]],<ref name=\"NYUMEDICAL\">[http://www.med.nyu.edu/biosketch/sheinj03 \"Bio: Dr. Jonathan Sheindlin\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150114004543/http://www.med.nyu.edu/biosketch/sheinj03 |date=January 14, 2015 }}, NYU Langone Medical Center</ref> and Greg and Nicole are lawyers. Nicole is the co-creator (along with her stepmother) of the Her Honor Mentoring program.\n\nSheindlin owns homes in several states, including [[Connecticut]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/06182008/gossip/cindy/dont_judge_judy_by_her_pricey_digs_115981.htm |title=Don't Judge Judy by her Pricey Digs |date=June 18, 2008 |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |work=The New York Post |author=Adams, Cindy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915003952/http://www.nypost.com/seven/06182008/gossip/cindy/dont_judge_judy_by_her_pricey_digs_115981.htm |archivedate=September 15, 2008 }}</ref> New York,<ref name=\"cbs\" /> Florida,<ref>{{cite video |people=Paul O'Grady (host) |date=October 2008 |title=Judge Judy on Paul O'Grady |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mKSGrczEoLI |medium=Television production |publisher=Granada Television |location=United Kingdom |accessdate=December 23, 2008}}</ref> and [[Wyoming]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Associated |first=The |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=171371497 |title='Judge Judy' Ruling Daytime TV |publisher=NPR |accessdate=February 8, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210005236/http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=171371497 |archivedate=February 10, 2013 }}</ref> She commuted to Los Angeles every other week for two to four days to tape episodes of ''Judge Judy''.<ref name=\"nydn\" /><ref name=\"cbs\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/04/28/60II/main551386.shtml |title=Judge Judy |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |date=December 10, 2003 |publisher=CBS |author=Leung, Rebecca}}</ref> However, in May 2013, she bought a $10.7 million [[condominium]] in the Los Angeles suburb of [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hauteliving.com/2013/05/judge-judy-buys-10.7-million-condo-in-beverly-hills/360784/ |title=Judge Judy Buys $10.7 Million Condo in Beverly Hills |publisher=Hauteliving.com |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202440/http://hauteliving.com/2013/05/judge-judy-buys-10.7-million-condo-in-beverly-hills/360784/ |archivedate=October 29, 2013 }}</ref> In 2018, Judy and her husband announced spending $9 million on the Bird House, a 9,700-square-foot property on 3.67 acres in Newport, Rhode Island that was owned by [[Dorrance Hill Hamilton]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Larson|first=Robert E.|last2=Hamilton|first2=James A.|last3=Bronson|first3=Dorrance C.|date=1959|title=Pensions|journal=The Journal of Insurance|volume=26|issue=2|pages=72|doi=10.2307/250676|issn=1047-3483|jstor=250676}}</ref>\n\nSheindlin holds honorary [[Doctor of Law]] degrees from [[Elizabethtown College]] and the [[University at Albany, SUNY]].<ref name=\"judgejudy.com\"/>\n\nSheindlin is a registered Independent.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Judith Susan Sheindlin's Florida Voter Registration |publisher=Voterrecords.com |url=https://voterrecords.com/voter/8954580/judith-sheindlin}}</ref> She is a supporter of [[same-sex marriage]] and,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> although she has said that she is not a supporter of \"[[big government]]\", she believes that the issue of same-sex marriage should be handled at the federal level rather than on a state-by-state basis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jqg80PfdtR4 |title=The View}}</ref> Sheindlin has stated that she is in favor of [[Gun politics in the United States|increasing requirements for gun ownership]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=King|first1=Larry|title=Judge Judy On Gun Control. Her Biggest Regret & Working 5 Days A Month|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y3GzfNRo5WY|accessdate=1 May 2018|date=July 30, 2012|via=YouTube}}</ref> She prefers not to be labelled by political terms, and states that she is not registered with any political party.  When asked about the 2012 presidential elections, Sheindlin stated that while she voted for President [[Barack Obama]] in 2008 (as well as voting for [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[Bill Clinton]], respectively in 1980 and 1984, and 1992 and 1996), she did not care for either of the leading candidates in the [[2012 United States presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ora.tv/larrykingnow/judge-judy-0_cl90x14u |title=Judge Judy Interview &#124; Ora TV |publisher=ora.tv |date=December 10, 2013 |accessdate=March 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130172239/http://www.ora.tv/larrykingnow/judge-judy-0_cl90x14u |archivedate=January 30, 2013 }}</ref> In October 2019 Sheindlin penned an op-ed endorsing [[Michael Bloomberg]] for president, despite the fact that he had not announced a campaign.<ref name=\"USAT\">{{cite web | last=Sheindlin | first=Judy | title=Judge Judy endorses Michael Bloomberg for 2020 presidential election | website=usatoday | date=Oct 16, 2019 | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2019/10/16/judge-judy-michael-bloomberg-presidential-race-2020-column/3984012002/ | access-date=Feb 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NYP2020\">{{cite web | title=Judge Judy endorses Mike Bloomberg for president | website=New York Post | date=Jan 6, 2020 | url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/06/judge-judy-endorses-mike-bloomberg-for-president/ | access-date=Feb 23, 2020}}</ref> In January 2020 she released an ad supporting him saying, in part, \"I like to say you can judge someone's character by what they've done; Mike Bloomberg has done amazing things, and will be a truly great president\".<ref name=\"NYP2020\"/><ref name=\"Cole 2020\">{{cite web | last=Cole | first=Devan | title=Judge Judy issues opinion on 2020 race, backs Bloomberg's presidential bid | website=CNN | date=Jan 6, 2020 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/06/politics/judge-judy-michael-bloomberg-endorsement/index.html | access-date=Feb 23, 2020}}</ref> She later campaigned alongside him.<ref name=\"NYP2020 2\">{{cite web | title='It's like when Oprah endorsed Obama': Judge Judy on campaign trail with Bloomberg | website=New York Post | date=Feb 22, 2020 | url=https://nypost.com/2020/02/22/its-like-when-oprah-endorsed-obama-judge-judy-on-campaign-trail-with-bloomberg/ | access-date=Feb 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Legal issues ===\nIn March 2013, a [[lawsuit]] was filed against Sheindlin by Patrice Jones, the estranged wife of Randy Douthit, executive producer of the ''Judge Judy'' court show. Jones alleged Douthit and Sheindlin had conspired to permit Sheindlin to buy [[Christofle]] [[porcelain|fine china]] and Marley [[cutlery]] owned by Jones. She said Sheindlin had paid Douthit $50,815 for the items without her knowledge to deprive her of her valuables,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/judge-judy-sued-ex-friend-china-cutlery-sets-article-1.1289099 |title=Ex-friend of Judge Judy: I'll drop lawsuit if you give back my china set |work=Daily News |location=New York |accessdate=March 15, 2013}}</ref> and she sought $514,421 from Sheindlin. The suit was settled out of court after Sheindlin returned the tableware to Douthit, and Jones agreed to pay him $12,500 and have the tableware handed back to her.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2013/03/16/judge-judy-settles-china-lawsuit-producer-dishes-flatware/ |title=Judge Judy China Lawsuit SETTLES! |publisher=TMZ.com |accessdate=March 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2014, Sheindlin filed a lawsuit for the first time in her life. It was filed against [[Hartford, Connecticut]] [[personal injury lawyer]] John Haymond and his [[law firm]]. In the lawsuit, Sheindlin accused Haymond and his firm of using her television image without consent in [[advertisement]]s that falsely suggested she endorsed him and his firm. Sheindlin's producer allegedly told the firm that use of her image is not permitted in March 2013, but ads continued to be produced. The lawsuit filed in [[United States federal court|federal court]] sought more than $75,000 in damages. Sheindlin said in her statement that any money she wins through the lawsuit will go toward college scholarships through the Her Honor Mentoring program. Sheindlin further stated, \"Mr. Haymond is a lawyer and should know better. The unauthorized use of my name is outrageous and requires legal action.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2014/03/12/judge-judy-lawsuit-lawyer/ |title=Judge Judy Sues P.I. Lawyer&nbsp;\u2013 You Have 'Stupid' on Your Forehead ... Stupid |publisher=TMZ.com |date=March 6, 2014 |accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=AP 6:59 p.m. EDT March 12, 2014 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2014/03/12/judge-judy-files-suit-against-connecticut-lawyer/6344599/ |title=Tables turned: Judge Judy files suit against lawyer |work=USA Today |accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.courant.com/2014-03-12/news/hc-judge-judy-haymond-lawsuit-20140312_1_judith-sheindlin-judge-judy-advertisements |title=Judge Judy Sues Local Personal-Injury Lawyer&nbsp;\u2013 Hartford Courant |publisher=Articles.courant.com |accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref> Haymond later filed a countersuit for [[punitive damages]] and [[attorney's fee]]s, alleging [[United States defamation law|defamation]] of him and his firm by Sheindlin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2014/08/08/judge-judy-settles-lawsuit-with-connecticut-lawyer/|title=Judge Judy settles lawsuit with Connecticut lawyer|first=Associated|last=Press|date=August 8, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> Haymond insisted that local affiliates asked him to appear in ''Judge Judy'' promos to promote Sheindlin for which he obliged.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2014/03/13/judge-judy-lawyer-lawsuit-john-haymond-promotion/ |title=Judge Judy&nbsp;\u2013 P.I. Lawyer Fires Back ... I Wasn't Promoting Me, I Was Promoting You! |publisher=TMZ.com |accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.courthousenews.com/2014/07/14/69464.htm |title=Hartford Attorney Fires Back at Judge Judy |publisher=Courthouse News Service |date=July 14, 2014 |accessdate=July 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714221519/http://www.courthousenews.com/2014/07/14/69464.htm |archivedate=July 14, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On August 8, 2014, it was reported that the case between Sheindlin and Haymond settled out of court in a resolution that favored Sheindlin. Haymond will be donating money to Sheindlin's charity, Her Honor Mentoring.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2014/08/08/judge-judy-lawsuit-settlement-lawyer-tv-commercial/|title=Judge Judy Wins One for the Girls In Lawsuit against Lawyer|website=TMZ|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n*{{cite book |title=Don't Pee on My Leg and Tell Me It's Raining |url=https://archive.org/details/dontpeeonmylegte00shei |url-access=registration |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=1996 |publisher=Harper Collins |isbn=0-06-092794-1}}<ref name=\"judy\" />\n*{{cite book |title=Beauty Fades, Dumb Is Forever |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=1999 |publisher=Harper Paperbacks |isbn=0-06-092991-X}}<ref name=\"judy\" />\n*{{cite book |title=Keep It Simple, Stupid: You're Smarter Than You Look |url=https://archive.org/details/keepitsimplestu000shei |url-access=registration |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=2000 |publisher=Cliff Street Books |isbn=0-06-019546-0}}<ref name=\"judy\" />\n*{{cite book |title=Win or Lose by How You Choose |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=2000 |publisher=Harper Collins |isbn=0-06-028780-2}}<ref name=\"judy\" />\n*{{cite book |title=You're Smarter Than You Look: Uncomplicating Relationships in Complicated Times |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=2001 |publisher=Harper Paperbacks |isbn=0-06-095376-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/youresmarterthan00shei }}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=126755&page=1 |title=Judge Judy: You're Smarter Than You Look |date=August 20, 2001 |accessdate=November 19, 2011 |publisher=Good Morning America}}</ref>\n*{{cite book |title=What Would Judy Say? A Grown-Up Guide to Living Together with Benefits |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=2013 |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform |isbn=978-1-4839-3167-8}}<ref name=\"nypost1\" />\n*{{cite book |title=What Would Judy Say: Be the Hero of Your Own Story |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=2014}}\n\n== Footnotes ==\n\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Jazmine Hughes, [https://web.archive.org/web/20190620190056/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/20/magazine/judge-judy-tv.html \"Judge Judy is Still Judging You,\"] ''New York Times Magazine,'' June 20, 2019.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.whatwouldjudysay.com What Would Judy Say? website]\n*{{IMDb name|id=0005419}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071023085045/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20060215/judge_judy_060214/20060215?hub=Entertainment Judge Judy marks 10 years laying down the law], [[CTV News]], February 15, 2006\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/09/realitytv.television Biographical article from ''The Guardian''], October 9, 2008\n* {{EmmyTVLegends name|judith-sheindlin|Judge Judith Sheindlin}}\n\n\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Lifetime Achievement}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Law|Television|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheindlin, Judith}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American judges]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:American people of German-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American University School of Public Affairs alumni]]\n[[Category:American women judges]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Female critics of feminism]]\n[[Category:Jewish activists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American attorneys]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Legal scholars]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New York Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:New York (state) state court judges]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People from Naples, Florida]]\n[[Category:Television judges]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Women television personalities]]\n[[Category:James Madison High School (Brooklyn) alumni]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Women television producers]]\n[[Category:Women legal scholars]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American lawyer, judge, television personality, and author}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Judy Sheindlin\n| image              = Judge Judy Sheindlin VF 2012 Shankbone.JPG\n| caption            = Sheindlin at the 2012 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]\n| birth_name         = Judith Susan Blum\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1942|10|21}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = {{unbulleted list|[[American University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]) | [[New York Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Lawyer|judge|television personality|author|[[arbitrator]]}}\n| years_active       = {{unbulleted list | 1965\u20131982 (attorney) | 1982\u20131996 (judge) | 1996\u2013present (television personality)}}\n| known_for          = ''[[Judge Judy]]''\n| children           = 2\n| spouse             = Ronald Levy (m. 1964\u20131976)<br />[[Jerry Sheindlin]] (m. 1977\u20131990; m. 1991)\n| net_worth          = $500 million<ref>{{Cite web|last= Singer |first=Jenny  |authorlink=   |title=These Are America's Richest Self-Made Jewish Women |publisher=[[Jewish Daily Forward]]|date=July 12, 2018 |url=https://forward.com/schmooze/405267/these-are-americas-richest-self-made-jewish-women/  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Judith Susan Sheindlin''' (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' '''Blum'''; born October 21, 1942),<ref name=\"bio\" /> known professionally as '''Judge Judy''', is an American [[Prosecutor|prosecution lawyer]], former [[Manhattan]] family court judge, television personality, and author. Since September 1996, Sheindlin has presided over her own successful four-time [[Daytime Emmy Award]]\u2013winning [[court show#Arbitration=-based reality court show|arbitration-based court show series]], ''[[Judge Judy]]'', produced by [[CBS Television Distribution]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.biography.com/personality/judge-judy | website= [[Biography.com]] |accessdate=February 6, 2020 |publisher=Biography, A&E Television Networks |title=Judge Judy Biography - Judge, Author, Reality Television Star (1942\u2013)}}</ref> She stated on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' she would finish up with the series after the conclusion of the 2020/2021 season, which would mark a 25 year run, as she would be launching a new series titled ''Judy Justice'', which would be of a similar format.<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/judge-judy-sheindlin-judy-justice-scott-koondel-1203520868/|title=Judge Judy Sets Sights on Streaming, Cable Arena for Next Chapter with 'Judy Justice'}}</ref>\n\nSheindlin passed the New York state [[bar examination]] in 1965 and became a [[prosecutor]] in the [[family court]] system. In 1982 [[Mayor of New York|New York City Mayor]] [[Ed Koch]] appointed her as a judge, first in criminal court, then later as Manhattan's supervising family court judge in 1986.\n\nSheindlin is the longest-serving judge or arbitrator in courtroom-themed programming history, a distinction that earned Sheindlin a place in the ''[[Guinness World Records]]''.<ref name=\"etonline\">{{cite web |url=http://www.etonline.com/media/video/judge_judy_sets_a_guinness_world_record-171890/ |title=Judge Judy Sets a Guinness World Record! |publisher=Etonline.com}}</ref> She has additionally received a [[Lifetime Achievement Emmy]] for her work; during the 2019 awards ceremony, [[comedienne]] [[Amy Poehler]] referred to Sheindlin as \"the Jewish mother we all want\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/tv-movies/a27372453/judge-judy-amy-poehler-lifetime-achievement-award-daytime-emmys/|title=Amy Poehler Fan Girls Over Judge Judy at the Daytime Emmy Awards|date=May 6, 2019|first=Emma|last=Dibdin|accessdate=April 8, 2020|publisher=[[OprahMag.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSheindlin was born Judith Susan Blum in the [[Brooklyn]] [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of [[New York City]], to a [[Jewish]] family, from Germany, Russia, and Ukraine.<ref name=CTRL-F-Jewish-passsge>{{cite web|url=https://forward.com/sisterhood/210866/life-love-and-the-proverbs-of-judge-judy/|title=Life, Love and the Proverbs of Judge Judy|website=[[The Forward]]|access-date=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=CTRL-F-Jewish-subheader>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/International/Order-in-her-court-Judge-Judith-Judy-Sheindlin-504679|title=#39 Judy Sheindlin - Order in her court - International news |website=[[Jerusalem Post]] |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=Facts>{{cite news |url=http://www.lawfuel.com/blog/judge-judy/|title=24 Facts and Things You Never Knew About Judge Judy|access-date=August 5, 2018|work=LawFuel|date=January 20, 2016|location=New Zealand}}</ref> She described her father as \"the greatest thing since sliced bread\" and her mother as \"a meat and potatoes kind of gal.\"<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/09/realitytv.television|title=Judy, madly, deeply|access-date=December 14, 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Weldon|first=Fay|author-link=Fay Weldon|date=October 9, 2008|location=London}}</ref>\n\nSheindlin attended [[James Madison High School (Brooklyn)|James Madison High School]] in Brooklyn before going on to [[American University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], where she graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree, majoring in government. She finished her law school education at [[New York Law School]], where she earned her [[Juris Doctor]] degree in 1965.<ref name=\"judy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.judgejudy.com/bios|title=Judge Judith Sheindlin: Presiding Judge|access-date=November 19, 2011|publisher=[[CBS Television Distribution]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSheindlin passed the New York state [[bar examination]] in 1965, the same year as her graduation, and was hired as a [[corporate lawyer]] for a cosmetics firm.<ref name=\"bio\" /> Within two years she became dissatisfied with her job and left to raise her two children. She was made aware of a position in the New York court system as a prosecutor in the family courts in 1972.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In her role as a lawyer, Sheindlin prosecuted child abuse cases, domestic violence and juvenile crime.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nBy 1982, Sheindlin's \"no-nonsense\" attitude inspired New York Mayor [[Ed Koch]] to appoint her as a criminal court judge.<ref name=\"bio\" /> Four years later, she was promoted to supervising judge in the family court's Manhattan division.<ref name=\"bio\" /> She earned a reputation as a \"tough\" judge (though she has disagreed with the labels \"tough\" and \"harsh\"),<ref name=\"wdrb.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/19965962/judge-judy-explains-how-she-can-tell-someone-is-lying |title=Judge Judy explains how she can tell someone is lying&nbsp;\u2013 WDRB 41 Louisville&nbsp;\u2013 News, Weather, Sports Community |website=Wdrb.com |accessdate=December 21, 2012}}</ref> known for her fast decision-making and acerbic wit.<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n\nIn February 1993, Sheindlin's outspoken reputation made her the subject of a ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' article,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1993-02-14/news/vw-307_1_family-court |title=Law and Disorder |first=Josh |last=Getlin |work=Los Angeles Times |date=February 14, 1993}}</ref> profiling her as a woman determined to make the court system work for the common good.<ref name=\"bio\" /> She subsequently was featured in a segment on CBS's ''[[60 Minutes]]'' that brought her national recognition.<ref name=\"bio\" /> This led to her first book, ''Don't Pee on My Leg and Tell Me It's Raining'', published in 1996. She retired as a family court judge that same year after having heard more than 20,000 cases.<ref name=\"bio\" /> \n\n===''Judge Judy'' ===\n{{Main|Judge Judy}}\n\n[[File:Judge Judy next to painting.jpg|thumb|right|Judge Judy stands next to a portrait of herself (2005)]]\n\nAfter the ''60 Minutes'' special on her family court career in 1993 and authoring her first book shortly thereafter (''Don't Pee on My Leg and Tell Me It's Raining''), Sheindlin was approached about starring in a new [[reality television#Reality court shows|reality]] courtroom series, featuring \"real cases with real rulings.\"<ref name=\"judy\" /> She accepted the offer, and her ongoing [[Television syndication|syndicated]] court show, ''Judge Judy'', debuted on September 16, 1996.<ref name=\"Stun Creative\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stuncreative.com/buster/cbs-judge-judy-20th-anniversary/|title=CBS JUDGE JUDY 20TH ANNIVERSARY |publisher=Stun Creative |date= |accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref> The court show's present 24th season commenced on September 9, 2019. \n\nSince its debut, ''Judge Judy'' has remained the No. 1 rated court show<ref name=\"nydn\" /> and regularly draws approximately 9 to 10 million viewers daily.<ref name=\"ppg\">{{cite news |work=The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |accessdate=December 24, 2008 |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08359/937221-42.stm |title=There's no justice like show justice |author=Leroux, Charles |date=December 24, 2008}}</ref> During the 2009\u201310 television season, ''Judge Judy'' became the first TV series in nearly a decade to attract more daytime viewers than ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Highfill |first=Samantha |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/05/02/judge-judy-renewed-2015/ |title='Judge Judy' renewed through 2015 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> Since then, it has been the highest rated show in all of daytime television.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2010/09/20/judge-judy-kicks-off-15th-season-as-the-number-1-daytime-show-in-syndication-570011/20100920cbs03/ |title=Ratings&nbsp;\u2013 \"Judge Judy\" Kicks Off 15th Season as the No. 1 Daytime Show in Syndication |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |date=September 16, 1996 |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 2015, [[CBS Television Distribution]] and Judge Sheindlin extended their contract for another four seasons, adding to her current contract (which was set to expire after the 2016\u201317 season), meaning it will be on the air until at least the 2020\u201321 season.<ref>[https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/judge-judy-extends-big-bucks-contract-with-cbs-through-2020-1201444365/ \"'Judge Judy' Extends Big Bucks Contract With CBS Through 2020\"] ''Variety'', March 2, 2015</ref> At that point, as Judge Sheindlin revealed in a March 2020 appearance on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'', the series will conclude.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ramos |first=Dino-Ray |title=\u2018Judge Judy\u2019 Wraps After 25 Seasons, Sheindlin To Return With \u2018Judy Justice\u2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/judge-judy-ends-25-seasons-judy-sheindlin-judy-justice-ellen-degeneres-show-1202871873/ |website=Deadline |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAuthor [[Brendan I. Koerner]] has commented on the popularity of ''Judge Judy'':\n\n<blockquote>Court-show viewers don't seem to want moral conundrums or technical wrinkles. They love Sheindlin's show because she offers them a fantasy of how they'd like the justice system to operate\u2014swiftly, and without procedural mishaps or uppity lawyers. They get to see wrongdoers publicly humiliated by a strong authority figure. There is no uncertainty after Sheindlin renders her verdict and bounds off the bench, and there certainly are no lengthy appeals.<ref name=\"slate\">{{cite news |url=http://slate.com/id/2118556/ |title=Judge Judy |author=Koerner, Brendan I |work=Slate |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |date=May 27, 2005}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nA 2013 ''[[Reader's Digest]]'' poll supported Koerner's statements, revealing that [[Americans]] trusted Judge Judy more than all nine justices of the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]].<ref name=\"sullivan1\">{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Sean |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2013/05/17/jimmy-kimmel-asks-judge-judy-for-the-supreme-court-video/ |title=Jimmy Kimmel asks: Judge Judy for the Supreme Court? (VIDEO) |work=The Washington Post |date=February 24, 2011 |accessdate=May 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe program has integrated itself into American [[popular culture]].<ref name=\"judy\" /> In 2003, [[VH1]] named Sheindlin one of the \"200 Greatest Pop Culture Icons.\"<ref name=\"judgejudy2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.judgejudy.com/bios |title=Judge Judy Bio |website=Judgejudy.com |accessdate=May 19, 2013}}</ref> References to Sheindlin\u2014typically as \"Judge Judy\", though often [[satire|satirical]]\u2014have appeared in multitudes of television programs and other media, including ABC's ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'';<ref name=\"sullivan1\" /> Fox's ''[[The Simpsons]]'' as Judge Constance Harm (voiced by [[Jane Kaczmarek]]); NBC's ''[[Will & Grace]]''; UPN/The CW's ''[[America's Next Top Model]]''; NBC's ''[[The Weakest Link]]''; ABC's ''[[The Practice]]''; the ''[[Academy Awards]]''; the book ''America: A Citizen's Guide to Democracy Inaction'' by [[Jon Stewart]];<ref name=\"judy\" /> a skit by [[Vicki Lawrence]] portraying [[Thelma Harper]]/[[Mama's Family|Mama]] on ''\"[[Betty White]]'s 2nd Annual 90th Birthday\"'' celebration,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/movies-specials-more/video/categories/betty-whites-second-annual-90th-birthday-party/ |title=Video Gallery &#124; Movies & Specials &#124; All Videos: Newest |publisher=NBC |accessdate=March 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021100858/http://www.nbc.com/movies-specials-more/video/categories/betty-whites-second-annual-90th-birthday-party/ |archivedate=October 21, 2013 }}</ref> drag queen [[Bianca Del Rio]] portraying Judge Judy on ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'', etc.\n\nSheindlin has been parodied on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', ''[[The Simpsons]]'' as Judge Constance Harm, and ''[[The Amanda Show]]'' as Judge Trudy.\n\nThe ''Judge Judy'' courtroom series has earned Sheindlin numerous awards and honors, including a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in February 2006;<ref>{{cite web |website=Hollywood.com |accessdate=December 24, 2008 |url=http://www.hollywood.com/photo_gallery/Judge_Judy_Sheindlin_Hollywood_Walk_of_Fame_Ceremony/3525341# |title=Judge Judy Sheindlin Hollywood Walk of Fame Ceremony Photo Gallery}}</ref> induction into ''[[Broadcasting & Cable]]''{{'}}s [[Hall of Fame]] in October 2012;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/488448-The_Battle_to_Survive_at_the_Top.php |title=The Battle to 'Survive' at the Top&nbsp;\u2013 2012-08-13 04:01:00 &#124; Broadcasting & Cable |website=Broadcastingcable.com |accessdate=December 13, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203074626/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/488448-The_Battle_to_Survive_at_the_Top.php |archivedate=December 3, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/13/judge-judy-katie-couric_n_2123114.html |title=Judge Judy on Future: 'Every Stage In Your Life Has A New Adventure' |work=The Huffington Post |date=November 13, 2012 |accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref> being awarded [[vice president|vice presidency]] of the [[University College Dublin Law Society|UCD Law Society]] in April 2013;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/judge-judy-honoured-by-ucd-society-1.1355090 |title=Judge Judy honoured by UCD society&nbsp;\u2013 Irish News, World News & More &#124; The Irish Times&nbsp;\u2013 Tue, April 09, 2013 |work=The Irish Times |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> being presented with the Gracie Allen Tribute Award from the [[Alliance for Women in Media]];<ref name=\"judgejudy2\" /> being awarded the Mary Pickford Award by the Hollywood Chamber Community Foundation at the 2014 Heroes of Hollywood;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/contact-us/community/Heroes-of-Hollywood--266830821.html |title=Heroes of Hollywood Honors Judge Judy Sheindlin |website=[[NBC Southern California]] |date=July 11, 2014 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> etc.\n\nOne award Sheindlin had difficulty winning was a [[Daytime Emmy Award]]. By 2011, her program had been nominated 14 consecutive years without winning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/nightlinedailyline/2010/05/toughtalking-oprah-competititor-judge-judy.html |title=Allumination Filmworks Is Proud to Release the First DVD From Everyone's Favorite No\u2013Nonsense Judge&nbsp;\u2013 Judge Judy Sheindlin |website=Sys-con.com |accessdate=July 22, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontheredcarpet.com/Daytime-Emmys-2011:-Full-list-of-nominees/8125012 |title=Daytime Emmys 2011 nominations: See full list&nbsp;\u2013 06/17/2011 &#124; Entertainment News from |website=OnTheRedCarpet.com |accessdate=December 13, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819003504/http://www.ontheredcarpet.com/Daytime-Emmys-2011:-Full-list-of-nominees/8125012 |archive-date=August 19, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In mid-2012, an article from the ''[[New York Post]]'' reported that ''Judge Judy'' was snubbed by the award show by [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Legal/Courtroom Program|not even being nominated that year]] despite being the highest-rated court show.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/tv/emmys_snub_judge_judy_view_ish_girls_rYCz3u5L1qcxeuE5kW6LpN |work=[[New York Post]] |title=Emmys snub Judge Judy, 'View'ish girls |date=May 10, 2012}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' (ET) on May 3, 2013, Sheindlin said, \"I have my walls full of Daytime Emmy Award nominations.\" When ET's interviewer asked Sheindlin if she thought she would ever win the award, she replied:\n\n{{quote|I don't know. You know, somehow it would sort of break the spell. The show has been such a tremendous success that I'm almost afraid to think about winning\u2014because so many of those shows that did win are no longer with us. So I say to myself 'you want the Emmy or you want a job? (laughing) Which one do you want?'<ref name=\"etonline1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/133630_Judge_Judy_on_How_Celebrities_Are_Treated_in_the_Justice_System/ |title=Judge Judy on Celebrities and the Justice System |website=ETonline.com |date=April 29, 2013 |accessdate=May 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129031501/http://www.etonline.com/news/133630_Judge_Judy_on_How_Celebrities_Are_Treated_in_the_Justice_System/ |archivedate=January 29, 2014 }}</ref>}}\n\nOn June 14, 2013, ''[[Judge Judy]]'' won its first Daytime Emmy for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Legal/Courtroom Program|Outstanding Legal/Courtroom Program]], having received its 15th nomination.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enstarz.com/articles/19832/20130615/daytime-emmy-awards-2013-ellen-degeneres-show-sesame-street-judge.htm |title=Daytime Emmy Awards 2013: 'The Ellen DeGeneres Show', 'Sesame Street', 'Judge Judy' Win Awards: TV |website=Enstarz.com |date=October 22, 2012 |accessdate=June 17, 2013}}</ref> The program won again in 2016 and 2017. Sheindlin's status as longest-serving judge or arbitrator in courtroom-themed programming history rewarded her a place in the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' on September 14, 2015, as part of her court show's 20th-anniversary celebration.<ref name=\"etonline\"/>\n\n==== Longevity and retirement plans ====\nThe only court shows that outnumber ''Judge Judy''{{'}}s seasons are ''[[The People's Court]]'' and ''[[Divorce Court]]''\u2014both of which have suffered cancellation(s) and gone through multiple judges or arbitrators.\n\nOn March 30, 2011, Sheindlin was admitted to the hospital after she fainted on the set of her show while handling a case. She was released the next day, and it was later learned that she suffered a [[Transient ischemic attack|mini-stroke]].<ref>https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2011/05/04/judge-judy-says-she-thinks-she-suffered-a-mini-stroke/</ref> Regarding her retirement, Sheindlin has stated that it is up to her viewers and when they tire of watching the program, which she believes will inevitably happen one day. As of the present, however, Sheindlin has stated that fans still seem to be interested and taking something out of the court show.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/19965962/judge-judy-explains-how-she-can-tell-someone-is-lying |title=Judge Judy explains how she can tell someone is lying&nbsp;\u2013 WDRB 41 Louisville&nbsp;\u2013 News, Weather, Sports Community |website=Wdrb.com |accessdate=May 18, 2013}}</ref> Sheindlin admits the court show is \"seductive\" and hard to give up. Sheindlin said, \"I'm not tired. I still feel engaged by what I do, and I still have people who like to watch it.\"<ref name=\"nydn\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2008/01/29/2008-01-29_judge_judy_will_keep_warming_bench.html |title=Judge Judy will keep warming bench |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |date=January 29, 2008 |work=The New York Daily News |author=Huff, Richard}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Sheindlin announced that the 2020-21 season of the show will be the last, after 25 years. A new program, entitled \"Judy Justice\" is set to air in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/judge-judy-end-after-25-years-t174930|title=Judge Judy to end her show after 25 years \u2014 but she isn't leaving TV just yet|website=TODAY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\n====Salary ====\nIn 2005, Sheindlin's salary was US$15 million per year.<ref name=\"slate\" /> Her [[net worth]] at the beginning of 2007 was $95 million, and she ranked #13 on the ''[[Forbes]]'' top 20 richest women in entertainment.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Pictures: The Richest 20 Women in Entertainment: Judith \"Judge Judy\" Sheindlin |url=https://www.forbes.com/2007/01/17/richest-women-entertainment-tech-media-cz_lg_richwomen07_0118womenstars_slide_14.html |author=Goldman, Lea and Kiri Blakeley |work=Forbes |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |date=January 18, 2008}}</ref> In July 2010 when Sheindlin's contract was renewed, her salary increased to $45 million per year. It was later reported in October 2013 that Sheindlin is the highest-paid TV star, earning $47 million per year for ''Judge Judy'', which translates into just over $900,000 per workday (she works 52 days per year).<ref name=\"parade1\">{{cite web |author=Lindsay Lowe |url=http://www.parade.com/217711/linzlowe/happy-birthday-judge-judy-5-things-you-didnt-know-about-judy-sheindlin/ |title=Happy Birthday, Judge Judy! 5 Things You Didn't Know About Judy Sheindlin |website=Parade.com |date=March 14, 2012 |accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref>  According to Forbes, Sheindlin earned $147 million, pretax, in 2017.<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite web |author=Madeline Berg |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maddieberg/2018/11/26/the-worlds-highest-paid-tv-hosts-2018-judge-judy-presides-with-147-million/#aaf8fdb48d67/ |title=The World's Highest-Paid TV Hosts 2018: Judge Judy Presides With $147 Million |website=Forbes.com |date=November 26, 2018 |accessdate=November 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Other media appearances ===\nSince the success of Sheindlin's courtroom series, she has been interviewed on [[talk show|talk]] and [[news broadcasting|cable news]] broadcasts over the course of her career. These talk and cable news programs include ''Entertainment Tonight'', ''[[The Wendy Williams Show]]'',<ref name=\"wchstv\" /> ''[[Katie (talk show)|Katie]]'' (numerous appearances),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.katiecouric.com/on-the-show/2012/11/12/daytime-star-judge-judy/ |title=Judge Judy Like You've Never Seen Her Before&nbsp;\u2013 Katie Couric |website=Katiecouric.com |date=November 12, 2012 |accessdate=March 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121224094505/http://www.katiecouric.com/on-the-show/2012/11/12/daytime-star-judge-judy/ |archivedate=December 24, 2012 }}</ref> ''[[Larry King Live]]'' (numerous appearances),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://larrykinglive.blogs.cnn.com/category/judge-judy/ |title=Judge Judy&nbsp;\u2013 Larry King Live&nbsp;\u2013 CNN.com Blogs |publisher=CNN |date=February 17, 2010 |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'' (numerous appearances),<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=http://theview.abc.go.com/category/tags/judge-judy |title=The View &#124; Judge Judy |publisher=American Broadcasting Company |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Donny & Marie (1998 TV series)|Donny & Marie]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvclip.biz/video/KgaprbQLiAE/donny-marie-with-judge-judy.html |title=Donny & Marie With Judge Judy |website=Tvclip.biz |date=May 18, 2010 |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> ''[[The Talk (TV series)|The Talk]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author=Cathy |url=http://haveuheard.net/2010/10/the-talk-upcoming-guests-including-hilary-swank-and-judge-judy/ |title='The Talk' Upcoming Guests Including Hilary Swank and Judge Judy &#124; HaveUHeardHaveUHeard |website=Haveuheard.net |date=October 25, 2010 |accessdate=March 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314185713/http://haveuheard.net/2010/10/the-talk-upcoming-guests-including-hilary-swank-and-judge-judy/ |archivedate=March 14, 2013 }}</ref> ''[[The Tonight Show]]'', ''[[Dateline NBC]]'', ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'', etc.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbspressexpress.com/cbs-television-distribution/shows/judge-judy/about |title=Press Express &#124; Not Available |website=Cbspressexpress.com |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> On October 17, 1998, Sheindlin made a surprise guest appearance on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', comedically interrupting one of [[Cheri Oteri]]'s regular [[parody|parodies]] of her presiding on ''Judge Judy.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snltranscripts.jt.org/98/98cjudy.phtml |title=SNL Transcripts: Lucy Lawless: 10/17/98: Judge Judy |website=Snltranscripts.jt.org |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> Also as a result of her ''Judge Judy'' show stardom, she served as a judge for the [[Miss America 1999|1999 Miss America pageant]].<ref name=\"wchstv\">{{cite news|url=http://www.wchstv.com/synd_prog/judy/ |accessdate=December 24, 2008 |year=2000 |title=Judge Judy |publisher=WCHS-TV8 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720040832/http://wchstv.com/synd_prog/judy/ |archivedate=July 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nEarly on in her celebrity on February 21, 2000, the ''[[Biography (TV series)|Biography]]'' program aired a documentary film on Sheindlin, \"Judge Judy: Sitting in Judgment\" (later released on [[home video]]). This 60-minute documentary captured Sheindlin's entire life story (dating back to her childhood), legal career, authoring career, entertainment career, etc. The special also featured input from those closest to Sheindlin and those who knew her best.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/detail/tv-show.aspx?tvobjectid=191411&more=ucepisodelist&episodeid=2321878 |title=Biography Episode Guide 2000&nbsp;\u2013 Judge Judy: Sitting in Judgement |work=TV Guide |accessdate=March 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.nytimes.com/show/52248/Judge-Judy-Sitting-in-Judgment/overview |title=Judge Judy: Sitting in Judgment |accessdate=March 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415172748/http://tv.nytimes.com/show/52248/Judge-Judy-Sitting-in-Judgment/overview |archivedate=April 15, 2014 }}</ref> On December 23, 2008, Sheindlin shared about her life on ''[[Shatner's Raw Nerve]]'', in which she was interviewed by [[William Shatner]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/shatners-raw-nerve-2008/episode-6-season-1/judge-judy/296013 |title=Shatner's Raw Nerve Episode Guide 2008 Season 1&nbsp;\u2013 Judge Judy, Episode 6 |work=TV Guide |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> A year later in December 2009, Sheindlin again told the story of her life, legal career, authoring career, and entertainment courtroom career from an updated perspective in a two-hour interview for ''[[Archive of American Television]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/judith-sheindlin |title=Judith Sheindlin Interview |website=EmmyTVLegends.org |accessdate=March 20, 2013}}</ref> In a free-wheeling 60-minute interview conducted by [[Katie Couric]] on September 17, 2013, for the [[92nd Street Y]], Sheindlin elaborated on previously-undisclosed fun facts of her life story and long career in the family court.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_7p8LWbp8qM |title=Judge Judy with Katie Couric |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=November 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.92y.org/Event/Judge-Judy.aspx |title=Judge Judy with Katie Couric&nbsp;\u2013 92nd Street Y&nbsp;\u2013 New York, NY |website=92y.org |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=November 16, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918060653/http://www.92y.org/Event/Judge-Judy.aspx |archivedate=September 18, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nAs confirmed in January 2014, a new court show conceived by Sheindlin titled ''[[Hot Bench]]'' debuted on September 15, 2014. The courtroom series features a panel of three judges debating and deciding on cases brought to their TV courtroom. Stated Sheindlin, \"When my husband Jerry and I were in [[Ireland]] recently, we visited the courts and watched a three-judge bench, which I found both fascinating and compelling. I immediately thought what a terrific and unique idea for a television program that brings the court genre to the next level. We have assembled three individuals with extremely varied backgrounds to serve as the judges. They are smart and talented, with terrific instincts and great chemistry, and are sure to create a hot bench.\" The panel of judges consists of [[New York State Supreme Court]] judge [[Patricia DiMango]] and Los Angeles attorneys Tanya Acker and Larry Bakman (Bakman has since been replaced on ''Hot Bench'' by Michael Corriero). As with ''Judge Judy'', ''Hot Bench'' is executive-produced by Randy Douthit and produced by CBS Television Distribution.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/judge-judy-sheindlin-to-launch-new-court-show-in-the-fall-1201068123/ |title=CBS To Launch New Courtshow From Judge Judy in Fall |work=Variety |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/judge-judy-created-hot-bench-premiere-fall-features-trio-of-judges |title=Judge Judy-Created 'Hot Bench' to Premiere in the Fall |publisher=TheWrap |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> Sheindlin originally desired the title of her personal courtroom series to be ''Hot Bench'' before producers ultimately settled on ''Judge Judy''.<ref name=\"cbsnews1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/2100-500164_162-551386.h |title=Judge Judy |publisher=CBS News |date=February 11, 2009 |accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/shows/judge-judy |title=Judge Judy &#124; Archive of American Television |website=Emmytvlegends.org |accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/9512194705/big-ticket-sets-hot-bench |title=Big Ticket sets 'Hot Bench'&nbsp;\u2013 Tags: HOT Bench With Judge Judy Sheindlin (TV program) BIG Ticket Television (Company) |website=Connection.ebscohost.com |accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn August 31, 2016, it was reported that CBS has a scripted, semi-[[autobiography|autobiographical]] [[drama (film and television)|drama series]] in the works based on the life of Sheindlin. The program title will be ''Her Honor'' (which was a proposed title for Sheindlin's court show along with ''Hot Bench''). The show has been described as following the youngest judge in New York who, while proficient at handling family court cases, has a personal life that needs work. Executive producers of the program include Sheindlin herself, Chernuchin, Arnold Kopelson and Anne Kopelson. Chernuchin was a writer for the [[legal drama]] series ''[[Law & Order (franchise)|Law & Order]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/judge-judy-cbs-drama-series-her-honor-1201848403/ |title=Judge Judy Developing Scripted Series at CBS Based on Her Life (EXCLUSIVE) |publisher=Variety.com |accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2016/09/01/judge-judy-sheindlin-drama-pilot-her-honor-cbs/ |title=CBS, Judge Judy Team for Autobiographical Drama Series |publisher=Tvline.com |accessdate=September 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/judge-judy-drama-cbs-her-honor/ |title=CBS Is Developing an Autobiographical Drama About Judge Judy |publisher=Tvguide.com |accessdate=September 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Sheindlin created a game show called ''[[IWitness]]'' that debuted on July 10 and ran for 6 weeks. The game show puts the contestant's observational skills to the test, requiring them to view video clips and recall what they have witnessed faster than their competitors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.longislandpress.com/2017/07/11/iwitness-new-game-show-from-judge-judy-debuts/ |title=iWitness: New Game Show from Judge Judy Debuts |publisher=Long Island Press |accessdate=September 9, 2017}}</ref> On September 17, 2017, Sheindlin appeared on the series premiere of Fox News Channel's ''Objectified'' hosted by [[Harvey Levin]]. The program's first episode took an inside look at Sheindlin's life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2017/09/06/fox-news-channels-objectified-series-hosted-by-harvey-levin-to-premiere-featuring-judge-judy.html |title=Fox News Channel's Objectified Series Hosted By Harvey Levin, to premiere featuring Judge Judy |accessdate=September 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[National Enquirer]]'' issued a formal apology in the September 2017 edition of their magazine for false statements, [[defamatory|defaming]] Sheindlin as having cheated on her husband and suffering from [[Alzheimer's Disease]] along with [[brain damage]]. In addition, they apologized to her daughter Nicole Sheindlin for defaming her as having a jail record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalenquirer.com/celebrity/apology-regarding-judge-judy-nicole-sheindlin/ |title=Apology Regarding Judge Judy And Nicole Sheindlin |publisher=National Enquirer |last= Taylor |first=J.R. |date=September 20, 2017 |accessdate=January 28, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nSheindlin and her program appeared on a November 26, 2017 broadcast of ''[[Curb Your Enthusiasm]]'', presiding over a [[sketch comedy]] court case with [[Larry David]] as the plaintiff. The pseudo-Judge Judy case took the appearance of an actual case from Sheindlin's program, taking place from the show's courtroom set with trademarked voice-over briefs, theme music and audience response.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2017/11/27/judge-judy-makes-hilarious-guest-appearance-on-curb-your-enthusiasm.html |title=judge judy makes hilarious guest appearance on 'Curb Your Enthusiasm' |publisher=Foxnews.com |date=November 27, 2017 |accessdate=November 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Sheindlin appeared as a guest on ''[[Norm Macdonald Has a Show]]'' on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eponymousreview.com/3998/norm-macdonald-netflix-show-chevy-chase-m-night-shyamalan/|title=Norm Macdonald's Netflix show to guest Chevy Chase, Judge Judy, M. Night Shyamalan {{!}} Eponymous Review|website=www.eponymousreview.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Writing ===\nSheindlin has authored seven books. In 1995, Judge Sheindlin published her first book, ''Don't Pee On My Leg and Tell Me It's Raining'', in which she offers her insight into how and why the family court fails in its mission to impact shattered families. ''Beauty Fades, Dumb Is Forever'', her second book, was published in January 1999. Her first children's book entitled, ''Win or Lose By How You Choose'' was published in 2000, followed by ''You Can't Judge A Book By Its Cover'' the next year. Sheindlin's third book for adults, ''Keep It Simple, Stupid: You're Smarter Than You Look'', also on the ''New York Times'' best seller list, published in 2000, shares her wisdom and opinions on solving family issues.<ref name=\"judgejudy.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.judgejudy.com/bios|title=Judge Judy - Bio|website=Judge Judy|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> One of her more recent books, which hit shelves on April 25, 2013, was inspired by one of her advisory catch phrases encouraging romantic partners to be judicious with regards to [[domestic partnership]]s.<ref name=\"nypost1\">{{cite news |last=Adams |first=Cindy |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/pagesix/cindy_adams/judge_judy_on_domestic_love_Q6UBVoMDodIdshBxpFJs1H |title=Judge Judy's fifth book, \"What Would Judy Say? A Grown-Up Guide To Living Together With Benefits,\" is upon us |work=New York Post |date=April 25, 2013 |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> In September 2014, Sheindlin celebrated the opening of her 19th season by giving out her latest book, ''What Would Judy Say: Be the Hero of Your Own Story'', for free.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Non-media projects and community work===\nSheindlin, along with her stepdaughter Nicole Sheindlin, is the creator, director, and spokesperson for an alliance designed to empower women, entitled \"Her Honor Mentoring\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.herhonor.org |title=herhonor Mentoring |publisher=Her Honor Mentoring |accessdate=November 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.herhonor.org/about-us/history|title=Her Honor Mentoring - Mission + History|website=www.herhonor.org|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Sheindlin funded a space for public debate at the [[University of Southern California]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2017/09/13/judge-judy-usc-debate-forum/ |title=Judge Judy Funds Debate Forum At USC |publisher=CBSLos Angeles |accessdate=January 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1964, Blum married Ronald Levy, who later became a [[prosecutor]] in [[juvenile court]]. They moved to New York and had two children, Jamie and Adam,<ref name=\"bio\" /> and divorced in 1976 after 12 years of marriage.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nIn 1977, she married Judge [[Jerry Sheindlin]], who was an arbitrator on ''[[The People's Court]]'' from 1999 to 2001.<ref name=\"bio\" /> They divorced in 1990, partially as a result of the stress and struggles that Judy endured after her father's death that same year.<ref name=\"bio\" /> They remarried a year later. She has three stepchildren with Sheindlin: Gregory, Jonathan and Nicole, and 13 grandchildren.<ref name=\"bio\" /> Jonathan is a [[Eye surgery#Vitreo-retinal surgery|retinal surgeon]],<ref name=\"NYUMEDICAL\">[http://www.med.nyu.edu/biosketch/sheinj03 \"Bio: Dr. Jonathan Sheindlin\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150114004543/http://www.med.nyu.edu/biosketch/sheinj03 |date=January 14, 2015 }}, NYU Langone Medical Center</ref> and Greg and Nicole are lawyers. Nicole is the co-creator (along with her stepmother) of the Her Honor Mentoring program.\n\nSheindlin owns homes in several states, including [[Connecticut]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/06182008/gossip/cindy/dont_judge_judy_by_her_pricey_digs_115981.htm |title=Don't Judge Judy by her Pricey Digs |date=June 18, 2008 |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |work=The New York Post |author=Adams, Cindy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915003952/http://www.nypost.com/seven/06182008/gossip/cindy/dont_judge_judy_by_her_pricey_digs_115981.htm |archivedate=September 15, 2008 }}</ref> New York,<ref name=\"cbs\" /> Florida,<ref>{{cite video |people=Paul O'Grady (host) |date=October 2008 |title=Judge Judy on Paul O'Grady |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mKSGrczEoLI |medium=Television production |publisher=Granada Television |location=United Kingdom |accessdate=December 23, 2008}}</ref> and [[Wyoming]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Associated |first=The |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=171371497 |title='Judge Judy' Ruling Daytime TV |publisher=NPR |accessdate=February 8, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210005236/http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=171371497 |archivedate=February 10, 2013 }}</ref> She commuted to Los Angeles every other week for two to four days to tape episodes of ''Judge Judy''.<ref name=\"nydn\" /><ref name=\"cbs\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/04/28/60II/main551386.shtml |title=Judge Judy |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |date=December 10, 2003 |publisher=CBS |author=Leung, Rebecca}}</ref> However, in May 2013, she bought a $10.7 million [[condominium]] in the Los Angeles suburb of [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hauteliving.com/2013/05/judge-judy-buys-10.7-million-condo-in-beverly-hills/360784/ |title=Judge Judy Buys $10.7 Million Condo in Beverly Hills |publisher=Hauteliving.com |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202440/http://hauteliving.com/2013/05/judge-judy-buys-10.7-million-condo-in-beverly-hills/360784/ |archivedate=October 29, 2013 }}</ref> In 2018, Judy and her husband announced spending $9 million on the Bird House, a 9,700-square-foot property on 3.67 acres in Newport, Rhode Island that was owned by [[Dorrance Hill Hamilton]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Larson|first=Robert E.|last2=Hamilton|first2=James A.|last3=Bronson|first3=Dorrance C.|date=1959|title=Pensions|journal=The Journal of Insurance|volume=26|issue=2|pages=72|doi=10.2307/250676|issn=1047-3483|jstor=250676}}</ref>\n\nSheindlin holds honorary [[Doctor of Law]] degrees from [[Elizabethtown College]] and the [[University at Albany, SUNY]].<ref name=\"judgejudy.com\"/>\n\nSheindlin is a registered Independent.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Judith Susan Sheindlin's Florida Voter Registration |publisher=Voterrecords.com |url=https://voterrecords.com/voter/8954580/judith-sheindlin}}</ref> She is a supporter of [[same-sex marriage]] and,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> although she has said that she is not a supporter of \"[[big government]]\", she believes that the issue of same-sex marriage should be handled at the federal level rather than on a state-by-state basis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jqg80PfdtR4 |title=The View}}</ref> Sheindlin has stated that she is in favor of [[Gun politics in the United States|increasing requirements for gun ownership]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=King|first1=Larry|title=Judge Judy On Gun Control. Her Biggest Regret & Working 5 Days A Month|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y3GzfNRo5WY|accessdate=1 May 2018|date=July 30, 2012|via=YouTube}}</ref> She prefers not to be labelled by political terms, and states that she is not registered with any political party.  When asked about the 2012 presidential elections, Sheindlin stated that while she voted for President [[Barack Obama]] in 2008 (as well as voting for [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[Bill Clinton]], respectively in 1980 and 1984, and 1992 and 1996), she did not care for either of the leading candidates in the [[2012 United States presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ora.tv/larrykingnow/judge-judy-0_cl90x14u |title=Judge Judy Interview &#124; Ora TV |publisher=ora.tv |date=December 10, 2013 |accessdate=March 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130172239/http://www.ora.tv/larrykingnow/judge-judy-0_cl90x14u |archivedate=January 30, 2013 }}</ref> In October 2019 Sheindlin penned an op-ed endorsing [[Michael Bloomberg]] for president, despite the fact that he had not announced a campaign.<ref name=\"USAT\">{{cite web | last=Sheindlin | first=Judy | title=Judge Judy endorses Michael Bloomberg for 2020 presidential election | website=usatoday | date=Oct 16, 2019 | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2019/10/16/judge-judy-michael-bloomberg-presidential-race-2020-column/3984012002/ | access-date=Feb 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NYP2020\">{{cite web | title=Judge Judy endorses Mike Bloomberg for president | website=New York Post | date=Jan 6, 2020 | url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/06/judge-judy-endorses-mike-bloomberg-for-president/ | access-date=Feb 23, 2020}}</ref> In January 2020 she released an ad supporting him saying, in part, \"I like to say you can judge someone's character by what they've done; Mike Bloomberg has done amazing things, and will be a truly great president\".<ref name=\"NYP2020\"/><ref name=\"Cole 2020\">{{cite web | last=Cole | first=Devan | title=Judge Judy issues opinion on 2020 race, backs Bloomberg's presidential bid | website=CNN | date=Jan 6, 2020 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/06/politics/judge-judy-michael-bloomberg-endorsement/index.html | access-date=Feb 23, 2020}}</ref> She later campaigned alongside him.<ref name=\"NYP2020 2\">{{cite web | title='It's like when Oprah endorsed Obama': Judge Judy on campaign trail with Bloomberg | website=New York Post | date=Feb 22, 2020 | url=https://nypost.com/2020/02/22/its-like-when-oprah-endorsed-obama-judge-judy-on-campaign-trail-with-bloomberg/ | access-date=Feb 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Legal issues ===\nIn March 2013, a [[lawsuit]] was filed against Sheindlin by Patrice Jones, the estranged wife of Randy Douthit, executive producer of the ''Judge Judy'' court show. Jones alleged Douthit and Sheindlin had conspired to permit Sheindlin to buy [[Christofle]] [[porcelain|fine china]] and Marley [[cutlery]] owned by Jones. She said Sheindlin had paid Douthit $50,815 for the items without her knowledge to deprive her of her valuables,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/judge-judy-sued-ex-friend-china-cutlery-sets-article-1.1289099 |title=Ex-friend of Judge Judy: I'll drop lawsuit if you give back my china set |work=Daily News |location=New York |accessdate=March 15, 2013}}</ref> and she sought $514,421 from Sheindlin. The suit was settled out of court after Sheindlin returned the tableware to Douthit, and Jones agreed to pay him $12,500 and have the tableware handed back to her.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2013/03/16/judge-judy-settles-china-lawsuit-producer-dishes-flatware/ |title=Judge Judy China Lawsuit SETTLES! |publisher=TMZ.com |accessdate=March 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2014, Sheindlin filed a lawsuit for the first time in her life. It was filed against [[Hartford, Connecticut]] [[personal injury lawyer]] John Haymond and his [[law firm]]. In the lawsuit, Sheindlin accused Haymond and his firm of using her television image without consent in [[advertisement]]s that falsely suggested she endorsed him and his firm. Sheindlin's producer allegedly told the firm that use of her image is not permitted in March 2013, but ads continued to be produced. The lawsuit filed in [[United States federal court|federal court]] sought more than $75,000 in damages. Sheindlin said in her statement that any money she wins through the lawsuit will go toward college scholarships through the Her Honor Mentoring program. Sheindlin further stated, \"Mr. Haymond is a lawyer and should know better. The unauthorized use of my name is outrageous and requires legal action.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2014/03/12/judge-judy-lawsuit-lawyer/ |title=Judge Judy Sues P.I. Lawyer&nbsp;\u2013 You Have 'Stupid' on Your Forehead ... Stupid |publisher=TMZ.com |date=March 6, 2014 |accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=AP 6:59 p.m. EDT March 12, 2014 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2014/03/12/judge-judy-files-suit-against-connecticut-lawyer/6344599/ |title=Tables turned: Judge Judy files suit against lawyer |work=USA Today |accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.courant.com/2014-03-12/news/hc-judge-judy-haymond-lawsuit-20140312_1_judith-sheindlin-judge-judy-advertisements |title=Judge Judy Sues Local Personal-Injury Lawyer&nbsp;\u2013 Hartford Courant |publisher=Articles.courant.com |accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref> Haymond later filed a countersuit for [[punitive damages]] and [[attorney's fee]]s, alleging [[United States defamation law|defamation]] of him and his firm by Sheindlin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2014/08/08/judge-judy-settles-lawsuit-with-connecticut-lawyer/|title=Judge Judy settles lawsuit with Connecticut lawyer|first=Associated|last=Press|date=August 8, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> Haymond insisted that local affiliates asked him to appear in ''Judge Judy'' promos to promote Sheindlin for which he obliged.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2014/03/13/judge-judy-lawyer-lawsuit-john-haymond-promotion/ |title=Judge Judy&nbsp;\u2013 P.I. Lawyer Fires Back ... I Wasn't Promoting Me, I Was Promoting You! |publisher=TMZ.com |accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.courthousenews.com/2014/07/14/69464.htm |title=Hartford Attorney Fires Back at Judge Judy |publisher=Courthouse News Service |date=July 14, 2014 |accessdate=July 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714221519/http://www.courthousenews.com/2014/07/14/69464.htm |archivedate=July 14, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On August 8, 2014, it was reported that the case between Sheindlin and Haymond settled out of court in a resolution that favored Sheindlin. Haymond will be donating money to Sheindlin's charity, Her Honor Mentoring.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2014/08/08/judge-judy-lawsuit-settlement-lawyer-tv-commercial/|title=Judge Judy Wins One for the Girls In Lawsuit against Lawyer|website=TMZ|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n*{{cite book |title=Don't Pee on My Leg and Tell Me It's Raining |url=https://archive.org/details/dontpeeonmylegte00shei |url-access=registration |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=1996 |publisher=Harper Collins |isbn=0-06-092794-1}}<ref name=\"judy\" />\n*{{cite book |title=Beauty Fades, Dumb Is Forever |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=1999 |publisher=Harper Paperbacks |isbn=0-06-092991-X}}<ref name=\"judy\" />\n*{{cite book |title=Keep It Simple, Stupid: You're Smarter Than You Look |url=https://archive.org/details/keepitsimplestu000shei |url-access=registration |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=2000 |publisher=Cliff Street Books |isbn=0-06-019546-0}}<ref name=\"judy\" />\n*{{cite book |title=Win or Lose by How You Choose |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=2000 |publisher=Harper Collins |isbn=0-06-028780-2}}<ref name=\"judy\" />\n*{{cite book |title=You're Smarter Than You Look: Uncomplicating Relationships in Complicated Times |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=2001 |publisher=Harper Paperbacks |isbn=0-06-095376-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/youresmarterthan00shei }}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=126755&page=1 |title=Judge Judy: You're Smarter Than You Look |date=August 20, 2001 |accessdate=November 19, 2011 |publisher=Good Morning America}}</ref>\n*{{cite book |title=What Would Judy Say? A Grown-Up Guide to Living Together with Benefits |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=2013 |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform |isbn=978-1-4839-3167-8}}<ref name=\"nypost1\" />\n*{{cite book |title=What Would Judy Say: Be the Hero of Your Own Story |last=Sheindlin |first=Judith |year=2014}}\n\n== Footnotes ==\n\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Jazmine Hughes, [https://web.archive.org/web/20190620190056/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/20/magazine/judge-judy-tv.html \"Judge Judy is Still Judging You,\"] ''New York Times Magazine,'' June 20, 2019.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.whatwouldjudysay.com What Would Judy Say? website]\n*{{IMDb name|id=0005419}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071023085045/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20060215/judge_judy_060214/20060215?hub=Entertainment Judge Judy marks 10 years laying down the law], [[CTV News]], February 15, 2006\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/09/realitytv.television Biographical article from ''The Guardian''], October 9, 2008\n* {{EmmyTVLegends name|judith-sheindlin|Judge Judith Sheindlin}}\n\n\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Lifetime Achievement}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Law|Television|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheindlin, Judith}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American judges]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:American people of German-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American University School of Public Affairs alumni]]\n[[Category:American women judges]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Female critics of feminism]]\n[[Category:Jewish activists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American attorneys]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Legal scholars]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New York Law School alumni]]\n[[Categor