       = \n| latm                            = \n| lats                            = \n| latNS                           = \n| longd                           = \n| longm                           = \n| longs                           = \n| longEW                          = <!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n| postal_code_type                = <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n| postal_code                     = \n| area_code                       = \n| website                         = [http://125.209.91.254/CDGK/LinkClick.aspx?link=217&tabid=72 Orangi Town Page]\n| blank_name                      = Office Location\n| blank_info                      = Municipal Head Office Orangi Town No. 12, Karachi.\n| blank1_name                     = E-mail\n| blank1_info                     = orangi@karachicity.gov.pk\n| blank2_name                     = Contact\n| blank2_info                     = (021)36697869-36650833\n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n| extinct_title                   = Disbanded\n| extinct_date                    = 2011\n}}\n\n'''Orangi Town''' ({{lang-sd|\u0627\u064f\u0648\u0631\u0646\u06af\u064a \u067d\u0627\u0624\u0646}}, {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0627\u064f\u0648\u0631\u0646\u06af\u06cc \u0679\u0627\u0624\u0646}}}}) was a [[Towns in Karachi|Karachi borough]] in the northwestern part of the city that was named after the sprawling municipality of [[Orangi]]. Orangi Town was formed in 2001 as part of [https://web.archive.org/web/20081013065059/http://www.nrb.gov.pk/city_district/index.html The Local Government Ordinance 2001], and was subdivided into 13 [[Union councils of Pakistan|Union Councils]]. The Town system and was disbanded in 2011,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribe.com/2011/07/11/karachi%e2%80%99s-district-status-restored-notification-issued/|title=Karachi\u2019s district status restored, notification issued|last=Abbasi|first=Saeed|date=2011-07-10|website=The News Tribe|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and Orangi Town was re-organized as part of [[Karachi West District]] in 2015.\n\n== Location ==\nOrangi Town was bordered by [[New Karachi Town]] to the north across the Shahrah-e-Zahid Hussain, [[Gulberg Town, Karachi|Gulberg Town]] to the east across the [[Gujjar Nala]] stream, [[Liaquatabad Town]] to the south, and [[SITE Town]] to the west. There were 13 official neighborhoods, called Union Councils  \n\n== History ==\nThe federal government under [[Pervez Musharraf]], who seized power in a [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|1999 coup d'etat]], introduced local government reforms in the year 2000, which eliminated the previous \"third tier of government\" ([[Divisions of Pakistan|administrative divisions]]) and replaced it with the fourth tier ([[Districts of Pakistan|districts]]). The effect in Karachi was the dissolution of the former [[Karachi Division]] in 2001, and the merging of its five districts to form a new Karachi City-District with eighteen autonomous constituent towns including Keamari Town. In 2011, the system was disbanded but remained in place for bureaucratic administration until 2015, when the [[Karachi Metropolitan Corporation]] system was reintroduced. In 2015, Keamari Town was re-organized as part of [[District of West Karachi|Karachi West]] district\n\n== Localities within Orangi Town ==\n[[Baloch Goth]]<br />[[Bilal Colony]]<br />[[Chisti Nagar]]<br />[[Raees Amrohi Colony]]<br />[[Data Nagar]]<br />[[Ghabool Town]]<br />[[Ghaziabad (Karachi)|Ghaziabad]]<br />[[Hanifabad]]<br />[[Haryana Colony]]<br />[[Iqbal Baloch Colony]]<br />[[Madina Colony (Orangi Town)|Madina Colony]]<br />[[Mohammad Nagar]]<br />[[Mominabad]]<br />[[Mujahidabad]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Akhtar Hameed Khan]]\n* [[Al-Jabbar Welfare Association ]]\n* [[City District Government Karachi]]\n* [[Karachi Health and Social Development Association]]\n* [[Khasa Hills]]\n* [[Orangi Charitable Trust]]\n* [[Orangi Nala]]\n* 